Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.30,0:00:06.87,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Seeing is not believing.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.91,0:00:09.28,English1,,0,0,0,,Our senses can deceive us.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.31,0:00:12.11,English1,,0,0,0,,Even the stars are not what they appear to be.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.15,0:00:14.61,English1,,0,0,0,,The cosmos, as revealed by science,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.65,0:00:17.95,English1,,0,0,0,,is stranger than we ever could have imagined.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.98,0:00:22.45,English1,,0,0,0,,Light and time and space and gravity
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.49,0:00:24.46,English1,,0,0,0,,conspire to create realities
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.49,0:00:27.99,English1,,0,0,0,,which lie beyond human experience.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.03,0:00:30.03,English1,,0,0,0,,That's where we're headed.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.10,0:00:32.67,English1,,0,0,0,,Come with me.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.00,0:00:38.14,English1,,0,0,0,,Back in 1802, on a night like this,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.17,0:00:41.31,English1,,0,0,0,,the astronomer William Herschel strolled the beach
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.34,0:00:43.91,English1,,0,0,0,,on the English coast, with his son John.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.94,0:00:46.81,English1,,0,0,0,,Herschel was the first person ever
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.85,0:00:49.88,English1,,0,0,0,,to see into the deeper waters of the cosmic ocean.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.95,0:00:54.15,English1,,0,0,0,,There he glimpsed the magic trick
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.19,0:00:56.02,English1,,0,0,0,,that light does with time.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.06,0:00:57.92,English1,,0,0,0,,Father...
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.96,0:01:00.03,English1,,0,0,0,,do you believe in ghosts?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.06,0:01:01.86,English1,,0,0,0,,Why, yes, my son!
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.90,0:01:04.43,English1,,0,0,0,,You, you do?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.46,0:01:05.93,English1,,0,0,0,,I would not have thought so.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.97,0:01:09.67,English1,,0,0,0,,Oh, no, not in the human kind of ghost.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.70,0:01:11.44,English1,,0,0,0,,No... not at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.47,0:01:13.94,English1,,0,0,0,,But look up, my boy,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.97,0:01:16.78,English1,,0,0,0,,and see a sky full of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.81,0:01:18.88,English1,,0,0,0,,The stars, Father?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.91,0:01:20.51,English1,,0,0,0,,I do not follow.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.55,0:01:25.38,English1,,0,0,0,,Every star is a sun as big, as bright as our own.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.42,0:01:29.72,English1,,0,0,0,,Just imagine how far away from\Nus you'd have to move the Sun
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.76,0:01:33.39,English1,,0,0,0,,to make it appear as small and faint as a star.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.43,0:01:37.20,English1,,0,0,0,,The light from the stars travels very fast...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.23,0:01:38.70,English1,,0,0,0,,faster than anything...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.73,0:01:41.37,English1,,0,0,0,,but not infinitely fast.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.40,0:01:45.20,English1,,0,0,0,,It takes time for their light to reach us.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.24,0:01:48.37,English1,,0,0,0,,For the nearest ones, it takes years.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.41,0:01:50.98,English1,,0,0,0,,For others, centuries.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.01,0:01:53.48,English1,,0,0,0,,Some stars are so far away,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.51,0:01:57.55,English1,,0,0,0,,it takes eons for their light to get to Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.58,0:02:02.22,English1,,0,0,0,,By the time the light from some stars gets here,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.26,0:02:04.72,English1,,0,0,0,,they are already dead.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.76,0:02:09.33,English1,,0,0,0,,For those stars, we see only their ghosts.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.36,0:02:11.66,English1,,0,0,0,,We see their light,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.70,0:02:15.10,English1,,0,0,0,,but their bodies perished long, long ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.70,0:02:20.74,English1,,0,0,0,,John, I have seen further back in time
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.77,0:02:22.84,English1,,0,0,0,,than any man before me--
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.88,0:02:25.81,English1,,0,0,0,,millions of years into the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.22,0:02:31.18,English1,,0,0,0,,William Herschel was the first person to understand
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.22,0:02:33.85,English1,,0,0,0,,that a telescope is a time machine.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.89,0:02:36.36,English1,,0,0,0,,We cannot look out into space
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.39,0:02:38.92,English1,,0,0,0,,without seeing back in time.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.66,0:02:44.93,English1,,0,0,0,,In one second, light travels 300,000 kilometers,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.97,0:02:47.77,English1,,0,0,0,,or 186,000 miles.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.80,0:02:50.20,English1,,0,0,0,,That's nearly the distance from the Earth to the Moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.24,0:02:54.11,English1,,0,0,0,,So, the Moon is about one light-second away.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.14,0:02:56.04,English1,,0,0,0,,The next time you look at the Moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.08,0:02:59.14,English1,,0,0,0,,you'll be seeing one second into the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.25,0:04:41.85,English1,,0,0,0,,That Sun...
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.88,0:04:43.58,English1,,0,0,0,,it's not really there.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.62,0:04:45.55,English1,,0,0,0,,It won't actually be above the horizon
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.59,0:04:48.05,English1,,0,0,0,,for another two minutes.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.09,0:04:50.42,English1,,0,0,0,,The sunrise is an illusion.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.46,0:04:53.23,English1,,0,0,0,,Earth's atmosphere bends the incoming rays of sunlight
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.26,0:04:55.73,English1,,0,0,0,,like a lens or a glass of water.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.76,0:04:59.40,English1,,0,0,0,,So we see the image of the Sun\N{\i1}projected above the horizon...
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.43,0:05:01.63,English1,,0,0,0,,before the physical Sun is actually there.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.27,0:05:05.91,English1,,0,0,0,,That Sun behind me is a mirage.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.94,0:05:08.01,English1,,0,0,0,,No more real than the shimmering image
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.04,0:05:09.18,English1,,0,0,0,,that hovers in the distance
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.21,0:05:12.24,English1,,0,0,0,,over a desert road on a hot day.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.28,0:05:15.25,English1,,0,0,0,,Sunlight takes about eight minutes to reach Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.28,0:05:18.52,English1,,0,0,0,,so the Sun is eight light-minutes away.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.55,0:05:21.29,English1,,0,0,0,,From Earth, we can only ever see the Sun
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.32,0:05:22.99,English1,,0,0,0,,as it was eight minutes ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.23,0:05:26.59,English1,,0,0,0,,And another thing,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.63,0:05:28.86,English1,,0,0,0,,the Sun doesn't really "rise" at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.90,0:05:31.06,English1,,0,0,0,,The Earth turns and we turn with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.63,0:05:35.53,English1,,0,0,0,,It may not look like it,\Nbut right at this moment,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.57,0:05:37.94,English1,,0,0,0,,I'm moving faster than a jet plane
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.97,0:05:40.44,English1,,0,0,0,,and so are you and everyone on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.47,0:05:41.64,English1,,0,0,0,,While I'm at it,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.68,0:05:42.94,English1,,0,0,0,,that horizon...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.98,0:05:44.44,English1,,0,0,0,,it's not really there at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.48,0:05:46.78,English1,,0,0,0,,There's no edge.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.81,0:05:49.32,English1,,0,0,0,,The horizon is just another illusion.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.33,0:06:06.90,English1,,0,0,0,,The distance between Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.93,0:06:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and the outermost planet Neptune
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.04,0:06:11.50,English1,,0,0,0,,varies as the planets orbit the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.54,0:06:15.11,English1,,0,0,0,,On average, the light makes that trip in four hours.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.14,0:06:16.74,English1,,0,0,0,,So for us on Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.78,0:06:20.65,English1,,0,0,0,,the Neptune we see is always four hours in the past--
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.68,0:06:23.32,English1,,0,0,0,,four light-hours away.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.35,0:06:24.58,English1,,0,0,0,,But the distances to the planets,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.62,0:06:26.25,English1,,0,0,0,,even the farthest one...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.29,0:06:28.99,English1,,0,0,0,,are mere baby steps on a much grander scale
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.02,0:06:31.02,English1,,0,0,0,,of the stars and galaxies.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.86,0:06:39.33,English1,,0,0,0,,As soon as we leave the Sun's\N{\i1}immediate neighborhood,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.37,0:06:41.17,English1,,0,0,0,,we need to change the unitive distance
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.20,0:06:44.34,English1,,0,0,0,,from light-hours to light-years.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.37,0:06:46.87,English1,,0,0,0,,A light-year is the yardstick of the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.91,0:06:50.01,English1,,0,0,0,,A single one is nearly ten trillion kilometers,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.04,0:06:52.68,English1,,0,0,0,,or about six trillion miles.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.71,0:06:55.88,English1,,0,0,0,,It's a unitive distance, just like a meter or a mile.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.92,0:06:58.18,English1,,0,0,0,,It's the distance light travels in a year.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.22,0:07:02.02,English1,,0,0,0,,The nearest star to the Sun, Proxima Centauri,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.06,0:07:05.39,English1,,0,0,0,,is a little more than four light-years away from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.43,0:07:07.63,English1,,0,0,0,,How far away is four light-years?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.66,0:07:10.03,English1,,0,0,0,,NASA's Voyager spacecraft moves
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.06,0:07:13.97,English1,,0,0,0,,at more than 56,000 kilometers an hour.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.00,0:07:17.14,English1,,0,0,0,,Even at that astonishing speed, it would take Voyager
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.17,0:07:21.01,English1,,0,0,0,,more than 80,000 years to reach the nearest star.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.85,0:07:26.81,English1,,0,0,0,,And the stars of the Pleiades cluster,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.85,0:07:28.85,English1,,0,0,0,,400 light-years away.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.25,0:07:31.92,English1,,0,0,0,,The Ship of the Imagination
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.95,0:07:34.22,English1,,0,0,0,,is equipped with a highly unusual capability--
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.25,0:07:35.92,English1,,0,0,0,,one-of-a-kind, actually.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.96,0:07:39.26,English1,,0,0,0,,It makes it possible for us\Nto see what was happening
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.29,0:07:43.23,English1,,0,0,0,,when the light from a distant\Nstar or galaxy first set out
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.26,0:07:45.93,English1,,0,0,0,,on its long journey to Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.63,0:07:49.57,English1,,0,0,0,,♪ ♪
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.60,0:07:53.07,English1,,0,0,0,,When that light left the Pleiades, about 400 years ago,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.11,0:07:56.78,English1,,0,0,0,,Galileo was taking his first look through a telescope.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.81,0:07:59.41,English1,,0,0,0,,A few years later, he tried to\N{\i1}measure the speed of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.45,0:08:01.25,English1,,0,0,0,,but he couldn't do it.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.28,0:08:04.12,English1,,0,0,0,,He had a very clever plan,\N{\i1}but the technology of that era
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.15,0:08:07.12,English1,,0,0,0,,just wasn't good enough to\N{\i1}measure the motion of anything
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.15,0:08:09.66,English1,,0,0,0,,that moves as fast as light.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.79,0:08:14.09,English1,,0,0,0,,When we look at the Crab Nebula from Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.13,0:08:17.10,English1,,0,0,0,,we're seeing much farther back in time.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.13,0:08:19.60,English1,,0,0,0,,The Crab Nebula was once a giant star,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.63,0:08:22.10,English1,,0,0,0,,ten times the mass of the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.14,0:08:24.94,English1,,0,0,0,,until it exploded in a supernova.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.97,0:08:26.97,English1,,0,0,0,,At its heart is a pulsar,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.01,0:08:29.44,English1,,0,0,0,,a collapsed star the size of a city,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.48,0:08:31.91,English1,,0,0,0,,spinning 30 times a second.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.02,0:08:42.46,English1,,0,0,0,,This pulsar's whirling magnetic field
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.49,0:08:44.56,English1,,0,0,0,,whips nearby electrons into a frenzy,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.59,0:08:48.63,English1,,0,0,0,,accelerating them to almost the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.66,0:08:52.13,English1,,0,0,0,,They shine with a blue glow that\Nlights up the tendrils of gas
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.17,0:08:54.63,English1,,0,0,0,,still unraveling from the supernova.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.67,0:08:56.17,English1,,0,0,0,,The Crab Nebula
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.20,0:08:59.34,English1,,0,0,0,,is about 6,500 light-years from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.01,0:09:03.01,English1,,0,0,0,,According to some beliefs,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.04,0:09:05.48,English1,,0,0,0,,that's the age of the whole universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.51,0:09:09.15,English1,,0,0,0,,But if the universe were only 6,500 years old,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.18,0:09:12.25,English1,,0,0,0,,how could we see the light from anything more distant
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.29,0:09:14.09,English1,,0,0,0,,than the Crab Nebula?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.12,0:09:16.09,English1,,0,0,0,,We couldn't.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.12,0:09:17.99,English1,,0,0,0,,There wouldn't have been enough time for the light
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.03,0:09:20.66,English1,,0,0,0,,to get to Earth from anywhere farther away
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.69,0:09:24.50,English1,,0,0,0,,than 6,500 light-years in any direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.53,0:09:27.10,English1,,0,0,0,,That's just enough time for light to travel
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.13,0:09:30.97,English1,,0,0,0,,through a tiny portion of our Milky Way galaxy.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.00,0:09:32.20,English1,,0,0,0,,To believe in a universe
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.24,0:09:35.04,English1,,0,0,0,,as young as 6,000 or 7,000 years old
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.08,0:09:38.11,English1,,0,0,0,,is to extinguish the light from most of the galaxy,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.15,0:09:41.18,English1,,0,0,0,,not to mention the light from all the 100 billion
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.21,0:09:44.72,English1,,0,0,0,,other galaxies in the observable universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.28,0:10:16.38,English1,,0,0,0,,The center of our own galaxy
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.42,0:10:19.59,English1,,0,0,0,,is about 30,000 light-years from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.62,0:10:21.55,English1,,0,0,0,,The light we see today
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.59,0:10:25.06,English1,,0,0,0,,coming from the core of the Milky Way left there...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.09,0:10:26.99,English1,,0,0,0,,when our ancestors were perfecting a way
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.03,0:10:29.43,English1,,0,0,0,,to vanquish death...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.70,0:10:35.67,English1,,0,0,0,,by making art with the power
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.70,0:10:38.74,English1,,0,0,0,,to inspire those who would come\N{\i1}long after they were gone.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.77,0:10:40.87,English1,,0,0,0,,♪ ♪
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.71,0:10:50.35,English1,,0,0,0,,The light we see coming from the Sombrero Galaxy
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.38,0:10:53.79,English1,,0,0,0,,is 30 million years old.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.82,0:10:57.26,English1,,0,0,0,,Our ancestors were living in trees when that light started out.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.29,0:11:01.43,English1,,0,0,0,,They weighed about five kilos\Nand had long tails.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.46,0:11:03.96,English1,,0,0,0,,But even 30 million light-years away
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.00,0:11:08.23,English1,,0,0,0,,is still in our own cosmic backyard.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.80,0:11:14.11,English1,,0,0,0,,That galaxy is part of the Coma Cluster,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.14,0:11:17.38,English1,,0,0,0,,320 million light-years away.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.41,0:11:19.28,English1,,0,0,0,,What was going on back home
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.31,0:11:22.75,English1,,0,0,0,,when the light you are seeing\N{\i1}began its trip to Earth?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.32,0:11:27.55,English1,,0,0,0,,No familiar continents, oceans or rivers.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.59,0:11:31.79,English1,,0,0,0,,Our distant ancestors were just\Nleaving the water for the land.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.83,0:11:33.63,English1,,0,0,0,,That's pretty old light,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.66,0:11:36.70,English1,,0,0,0,,but not nearly the oldest light we can see.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.87,0:11:42.07,English1,,0,0,0,,The oldest light is very faint,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.10,0:11:44.24,English1,,0,0,0,,a pale ghost in the night.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.27,0:11:47.31,English1,,0,0,0,,See that red blob inside the circle?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.34,0:11:50.81,English1,,0,0,0,,That's one of the oldest\N{\i1}galaxies we've ever seen.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.84,0:11:55.85,English1,,0,0,0,,You're looking at 13.4-billion year-old starlight
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.88,0:11:59.69,English1,,0,0,0,,as captured by the Hubble space telescope.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.63,0:12:10.43,English1,,0,0,0,,It's coming from the very first generation of stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.46,0:12:13.00,English1,,0,0,0,,What was happening on Earth back then?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.03,0:12:15.17,English1,,0,0,0,,Absolutely nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.20,0:12:18.84,English1,,0,0,0,,There was no Earth, no Sun, no Milky Way.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.87,0:12:22.38,English1,,0,0,0,,They would not come to be for billions of years.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.88,0:12:27.85,English1,,0,0,0,,When we try to look even farther into the universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.88,0:12:31.18,English1,,0,0,0,,we come to what appears to be the end of space...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.22,0:12:35.05,English1,,0,0,0,,but actually...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.09,0:12:37.16,English1,,0,0,0,,it's the beginning of time.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.84,0:12:45.41,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Earth pulls on us.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.44,0:12:48.41,English1,,0,0,0,,Our lives are a relentless struggle with gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.93,0:13:05.23,English1,,0,0,0,,That little girl is trying her best to climb out
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.26,0:13:07.50,English1,,0,0,0,,of a gravitational well.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.53,0:13:11.40,English1,,0,0,0,,From our first efforts to stand to our final surrender,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.44,0:13:14.91,English1,,0,0,0,,we are struggling to overcome the Earth's pull.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.94,0:13:19.84,English1,,0,0,0,,We are born, live and die in a force field--
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.88,0:13:24.28,English1,,0,0,0,,one that is almost as old as the universe itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.32,0:13:26.92,English1,,0,0,0,,And how old is that?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.95,0:13:30.52,English1,,0,0,0,,To visualize the 13.8 billion year age of the universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.56,0:13:32.09,English1,,0,0,0,,we've compressed all of cosmic time
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.12,0:13:34.59,English1,,0,0,0,,into a single year-at-a-glance calendar.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.63,0:13:39.43,English1,,0,0,0,,Midnight on December 31 is this very moment right now.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.46,0:13:43.47,English1,,0,0,0,,And January 1 is the beginning of time.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.50,0:13:45.87,English1,,0,0,0,,See that glowing fog out there?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.90,0:13:49.04,English1,,0,0,0,,It's radiation left over from the Big Bang,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.07,0:13:51.04,English1,,0,0,0,,the explosion that made the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.08,0:13:54.38,English1,,0,0,0,,13.8 billion years ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.41,0:14:00.32,English1,,0,0,0,,Right now, we're at the very\Nedge of known space and time.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.09,0:14:04.29,English1,,0,0,0,,So what happened before the Big Bang?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.32,0:14:05.96,English1,,0,0,0,,Nobody knows.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.99,0:14:08.79,English1,,0,0,0,,No evidence survives from before that moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.83,0:14:10.63,English1,,0,0,0,,We've got some pretty crazy ideas
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.66,0:14:12.13,English1,,0,0,0,,about where the universe came from,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.16,0:14:15.13,English1,,0,0,0,,which we'll get to, in time.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.17,0:14:18.07,English1,,0,0,0,,Where are we in the universe?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.10,0:14:21.17,English1,,0,0,0,,At the very center.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.21,0:14:25.14,English1,,0,0,0,,In the observed universe,\N{\i1}everyone gets to feel special.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.18,0:14:28.01,English1,,0,0,0,,No matter which galaxy you happen to live in,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.05,0:14:31.15,English1,,0,0,0,,when you look out to the\N{\i1}universe, you'll find yourself
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.18,0:14:34.49,English1,,0,0,0,,at the center of the cosmic horizon.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.52,0:14:36.49,English1,,0,0,0,,But this is just an illusion.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.52,0:14:38.36,English1,,0,0,0,,In reality, there is no center,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.39,0:14:40.83,English1,,0,0,0,,and the cosmic horizon is no more real
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.86,0:14:43.06,English1,,0,0,0,,than the horizon at sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.73,0:14:47.53,English1,,0,0,0,,It's what you get when you have a finite speed of light
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.57,0:14:50.87,English1,,0,0,0,,in a universe that had a beginning in time.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.87,0:14:56.84,English1,,0,0,0,,A few hundred million years after the Big Bang,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.88,0:15:00.01,English1,,0,0,0,,vast clouds of hydrogen and helium condensed
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.05,0:15:03.28,English1,,0,0,0,,into the first stars and galaxies.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.32,0:15:04.85,English1,,0,0,0,,With these new sources of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.88,0:15:07.89,English1,,0,0,0,,the long dark ages of the universe ended.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.92,0:15:10.45,English1,,0,0,0,,As space continued to expand,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.49,0:15:14.19,English1,,0,0,0,,cosmic evolution unfolded on grander scales.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.23,0:15:16.53,English1,,0,0,0,,As the first generation of stars died,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.56,0:15:19.86,English1,,0,0,0,,they seeded space with heavier elements,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.90,0:15:22.53,English1,,0,0,0,,making possible the formation of planets,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.57,0:15:25.74,English1,,0,0,0,,and ultimately, life.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.74,0:15:33.24,English1,,0,0,0,,Matter and energy were formed in the Big Bang.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.28,0:15:34.71,English1,,0,0,0,,But that's not all.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.75,0:15:37.21,English1,,0,0,0,,Space and time were created, too,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.25,0:15:39.55,English1,,0,0,0,,and all the forces that bind matter together,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.58,0:15:41.09,English1,,0,0,0,,including gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.12,0:15:43.49,English1,,0,0,0,,Isaac Newton discovered a mathematical law
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.52,0:15:45.89,English1,,0,0,0,,that describes how gravity works.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.92,0:15:49.23,English1,,0,0,0,,With that law, he could explain\Nthe motions of the planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.26,0:15:51.23,English1,,0,0,0,,More than 100 years later,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.26,0:15:55.47,English1,,0,0,0,,William Herschel realized gravity could do much more.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.44,0:16:04.74,English1,,0,0,0,,John, can you keep a secret?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.78,0:16:06.58,English1,,0,0,0,,Yes, Father.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.61,0:16:10.98,English1,,0,0,0,,I've made a discovery and have\Nyet to tell another soul.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.45,0:16:15.62,English1,,0,0,0,,The gravity that holds us to the Earth--
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.65,0:16:17.59,English1,,0,0,0,,the same gravity that Newton showed
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.62,0:16:19.52,English1,,0,0,0,,keeps the planets in their orbits--
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.56,0:16:21.09,English1,,0,0,0,,I've discovered
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.13,0:16:25.13,English1,,0,0,0,,that it also rules the distant stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.16,0:16:29.43,English1,,0,0,0,,Father... but how can you know this?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.47,0:16:31.84,English1,,0,0,0,,Can you find the constellation of the Lion?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.64,0:16:35.97,English1,,0,0,0,,There.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.01,0:16:37.31,English1,,0,0,0,,Well done.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.34,0:16:39.94,English1,,0,0,0,,Can you now find the star
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.98,0:16:43.28,English1,,0,0,0,,that joins the Lion's head to his body?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.32,0:16:44.62,English1,,0,0,0,,That one.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.65,0:16:47.99,English1,,0,0,0,,That star is really two stars
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.02,0:16:51.99,English1,,0,0,0,,so close together that they appear to be one.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.02,0:16:54.63,English1,,0,0,0,,I've been watching them through my telescope
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.66,0:16:56.99,English1,,0,0,0,,since long before you were born.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.00,0:17:01.90,English1,,0,0,0,,They dance around each other very slowly.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.93,0:17:06.20,English1,,0,0,0,,More slowly than any planet moves around the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.17,0:17:10.81,English1,,0,0,0,,Many of the stars we see tonight,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.84,0:17:12.81,English1,,0,0,0,,perhaps most of them,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.84,0:17:15.41,English1,,0,0,0,,dance with invisible partners.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.45,0:17:20.62,English1,,0,0,0,,Gravity's empire governs all the heavens.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.20,0:17:31.53,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}A century earlier,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.56,0:17:33.43,English1,,0,0,0,,Isaac Newton had been haunted
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.47,0:17:36.50,English1,,0,0,0,,by the same absence of a mechanism for gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.54,0:17:39.10,English1,,0,0,0,,How could distant bodies affect each other
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.14,0:17:42.87,English1,,0,0,0,,across empty space without actually touching?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.91,0:17:47.18,English1,,0,0,0,,This "action at a distance,"\N{\i1}as he called it, baffled him.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.88,0:17:52.35,English1,,0,0,0,,In the 19th century, Michael Faraday discovered
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.38,0:17:55.45,English1,,0,0,0,,that we were surrounded by invisible fields of force
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.49,0:17:58.19,English1,,0,0,0,,that explained how gravity works.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.22,0:18:00.79,English1,,0,0,0,,The apple and the Earth\N{\i1}don't touch each other,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.83,0:18:03.46,English1,,0,0,0,,but the fields between them do.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.50,0:18:07.03,English1,,0,0,0,,He imagined those lines of gravitational force
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.07,0:18:10.07,English1,,0,0,0,,radiating out into space\N{\i1}from every massive body--
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.10,0:18:15.37,English1,,0,0,0,,the Earth, the Moon, the Sun, everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.41,0:18:18.24,English1,,0,0,0,,Here was the answer to that question
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.28,0:18:20.88,English1,,0,0,0,,that had stumped Newton.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.91,0:18:25.65,English1,,0,0,0,,In 1865, James Clerk Maxwell\N{\i1}translated Faraday's idea
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.68,0:18:28.25,English1,,0,0,0,,about fields of electricity and magnetism
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.29,0:18:31.06,English1,,0,0,0,,into mathematical laws.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.09,0:18:35.09,English1,,0,0,0,,He discovered that these fields\N{\i1}move through space in waves.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.13,0:18:37.73,English1,,0,0,0,,When he calculated how fast they move,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.76,0:18:40.73,English1,,0,0,0,,it turned out to be the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.77,0:18:42.73,English1,,0,0,0,,We were beginning to discover the threads
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.77,0:18:44.57,English1,,0,0,0,,of the cosmic tapestry,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.60,0:18:47.67,English1,,0,0,0,,but we were not yet able\N{\i1}to discern the rich pattern
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.71,0:18:51.74,English1,,0,0,0,,that time, light, space and gravity weave.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.78,0:18:53.28,English1,,0,0,0,,As Albert Einstein worked in Berlin
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.31,0:18:55.11,English1,,0,0,0,,on his theory of gravity,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.15,0:18:58.85,English1,,0,0,0,,he kept the portraits of these three men before him.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.88,0:19:02.22,English1,,0,0,0,,He knew he was standing on their shoulders.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.25,0:19:05.22,English1,,0,0,0,,Years before, as a teenager, he had an insight
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.26,0:19:08.89,English1,,0,0,0,,that was as Earth-shaking as any idea of theirs.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.93,0:19:10.60,English1,,0,0,0,,And it happened one summer
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.63,0:19:13.46,English1,,0,0,0,,while he was daydreaming in Italy.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.06,0:19:20.86,English1,,0,0,0,,In the summer of 1895,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.90,0:19:23.70,English1,,0,0,0,,Einstein's father's business in Germany had failed,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.73,0:19:26.20,English1,,0,0,0,,and the family had moved here to northern Italy.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.24,0:19:29.04,English1,,0,0,0,,Young Einstein loved wandering these roads
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.07,0:19:31.88,English1,,0,0,0,,and giving his mind free rein to explore.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.91,0:19:35.58,English1,,0,0,0,,There's something timeless about this place.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.31,0:19:38.88,English1,,0,0,0,,Nothing here has really changed
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.92,0:19:41.92,English1,,0,0,0,,since the time of Einstein's early daydreams.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.26,0:19:49.56,English1,,0,0,0,,One day, he began to think about light
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.59,0:19:52.06,English1,,0,0,0,,and how fast it travels.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.10,0:19:54.30,English1,,0,0,0,,In everyday life, we always measure the speed
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.33,0:19:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,of a moving object with respect to something else.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.00,0:19:59.61,English1,,0,0,0,,Something that's presumably not moving.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.27,0:20:03.28,English1,,0,0,0,,Something in the cosmos that's not in motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.37,0:20:07.18,English1,,0,0,0,,For example, I'm moving about ten kilometers per hour
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.21,0:20:09.61,English1,,0,0,0,,relative to the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.65,0:20:12.68,English1,,0,0,0,,But as I mentioned earlier, the ground is moving.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.72,0:20:17.09,English1,,0,0,0,,Earth is turning at more than 1,600 kilometers per hour
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.12,0:20:18.86,English1,,0,0,0,,while it orbits the Sun
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.89,0:20:21.69,English1,,0,0,0,,at more than 100,000 kilometers per hour.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.73,0:20:24.09,English1,,0,0,0,,And the Sun is moving through the galaxy
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.13,0:20:27.16,English1,,0,0,0,,at a half a million miles per hour.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.20,0:20:29.37,English1,,0,0,0,,And the Milky Way is moving through the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.40,0:20:32.47,English1,,0,0,0,,at nearly one and a half million miles an hour.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:32.50,0:20:35.64,English1,,0,0,0,,There is no fixed place in the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.67,0:20:38.01,English1,,0,0,0,,All of nature is in motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.51,0:20:41.61,English1,,0,0,0,,It was hard even for the young Einstein
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.65,0:20:43.71,English1,,0,0,0,,to imagine some absolute standard
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.75,0:20:47.68,English1,,0,0,0,,to measure all those relative motions against.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.20,0:21:02.80,English1,,0,0,0,,This is the very book
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.83,0:21:05.24,English1,,0,0,0,,that inspired Einstein as a young boy.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.87,0:21:10.01,English1,,0,0,0,,Give a kid a book and you change the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.04,0:21:12.34,English1,,0,0,0,,In a way, even the universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.38,0:21:15.91,English1,,0,0,0,,Look at this-- the very first page,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.95,0:21:17.81,English1,,0,0,0,,it describes the astonishing speed
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.85,0:21:19.58,English1,,0,0,0,,of electricity through wires
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.62,0:21:22.19,English1,,0,0,0,,and light through space.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.22,0:21:25.79,English1,,0,0,0,,Einstein remembered what he'd learned as a child\Nfrom this book
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.86,0:21:29.26,English1,,0,0,0,,and perhaps, for the first time, right here,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.29,0:21:30.93,English1,,0,0,0,,wondered what the world would look like
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.96,0:21:33.90,English1,,0,0,0,,if you could travel at the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.70,0:21:40.17,English1,,0,0,0,,The more Einstein thought about it,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.20,0:21:42.07,English1,,0,0,0,,the more troubled he became.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.11,0:21:45.41,English1,,0,0,0,,If you imagine traveling at the speed of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.44,0:21:49.28,English1,,0,0,0,,paradoxes seem to pop up everywhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.31,0:21:52.08,English1,,0,0,0,,Einstein was shocked to realize that so much
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.12,0:21:54.12,English1,,0,0,0,,of what had been uncritically accepted as truth
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.15,0:21:56.69,English1,,0,0,0,,by even the greatest authorities on the subject
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.72,0:21:58.29,English1,,0,0,0,,was just plain wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:59.96,0:22:02.29,English1,,0,0,0,,When traveling at high speeds,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.33,0:22:05.26,English1,,0,0,0,,there are certain rules which must be obeyed.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.30,0:22:08.03,English1,,0,0,0,,Einstein called these rules "The Principles of Relativity."
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.07,0:22:10.73,English1,,0,0,0,,Imagine that young woman who just blew past us
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.77,0:22:12.20,English1,,0,0,0,,on the motorbike,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.24,0:22:13.70,English1,,0,0,0,,imagine she was riding her bike
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.74,0:22:16.74,English1,,0,0,0,,through the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.77,0:22:19.38,English1,,0,0,0,,Light from a moving object travels
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.41,0:22:21.38,English1,,0,0,0,,at the same speed, no matter whether the object
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.41,0:22:24.28,English1,,0,0,0,,is at rest or in motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.32,0:22:27.22,English1,,0,0,0,,Her speed is not added to the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.25,0:22:29.05,English1,,0,0,0,,The light from her motorbike
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.09,0:22:31.65,English1,,0,0,0,,still travels at the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.29,0:22:35.06,English1,,0,0,0,,Nature commands,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.09,0:22:38.90,English1,,0,0,0,,"Thou shalt not add my speed to the speed of light."
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.93,0:22:41.46,English1,,0,0,0,,Also, no material object
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.50,0:22:44.07,English1,,0,0,0,,can travel at or faster than the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.10,0:22:46.17,English1,,0,0,0,,There's nothing in physics that prevents you
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.20,0:22:48.77,English1,,0,0,0,,from traveling as close to the speed of light as you like.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.81,0:22:52.44,English1,,0,0,0,,99.9% of the speed of light is just fine,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.48,0:22:54.91,English1,,0,0,0,,but no matter how hard you try,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.95,0:22:57.41,English1,,0,0,0,,you never gain that last decimal point.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.45,0:23:00.25,English1,,0,0,0,,For reality to be logically consistent,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.28,0:23:02.85,English1,,0,0,0,,there must be a cosmic speed limit.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.13,0:23:12.60,English1,,0,0,0,,The crack of that whip is due to its tip
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.63,0:23:14.60,English1,,0,0,0,,moving faster than the speed of sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.63,0:23:16.43,English1,,0,0,0,,It makes a shockwave,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.47,0:23:18.84,English1,,0,0,0,,a mini sonic boom,\Nin the Italian countryside.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.67,0:23:23.84,English1,,0,0,0,,A thunderclap works the same way,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.87,0:23:26.98,English1,,0,0,0,,and so does the sound of a passing supersonic jet.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.01,0:23:29.31,English1,,0,0,0,,So why is the speed of light
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.35,0:23:31.48,English1,,0,0,0,,any more a barrier than the speed of sound?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.52,0:23:34.22,English1,,0,0,0,,The answer is not just that light travels
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.25,0:23:36.45,English1,,0,0,0,,about a million times faster than sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.49,0:23:38.89,English1,,0,0,0,,And it's not merely an engineering problem,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.92,0:23:40.46,English1,,0,0,0,,like building the first supersonic jet.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.49,0:23:42.86,English1,,0,0,0,,Instead, the light barrier
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.89,0:23:44.79,English1,,0,0,0,,is a fundamental law of nature,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.83,0:23:46.66,English1,,0,0,0,,as basic as gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.70,0:23:49.97,English1,,0,0,0,,Einstein found his absolute framework for the world,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.00,0:23:52.04,English1,,0,0,0,,this sturdy pillar among all the relative motions
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.07,0:23:54.74,English1,,0,0,0,,within the motions of the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.77,0:23:56.54,English1,,0,0,0,,Light travels just as fast,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:56.57,0:24:00.71,English1,,0,0,0,,no matter how fast or slow its source is moving.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.74,0:24:04.71,English1,,0,0,0,,Speed of light is constant, relative to everything else.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.75,0:24:07.02,English1,,0,0,0,,Nothing can ever catch up with light.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.22,0:24:11.32,English1,,0,0,0,,The thing about the laws of nature
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.36,0:24:13.22,English1,,0,0,0,,is that they're unbreakable.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.26,0:24:16.23,English1,,0,0,0,,The job of physicists is to discover these commandments,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.26,0:24:19.20,English1,,0,0,0,,the ones that do not vary from culture to culture
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.23,0:24:20.86,English1,,0,0,0,,or time to time
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.90,0:24:23.00,English1,,0,0,0,,and hold true throughout the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.03,0:24:26.10,English1,,0,0,0,,That's why, as Einstein showed,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.14,0:24:29.77,English1,,0,0,0,,funny things happen close to the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.98,0:24:35.88,English1,,0,0,0,,Traveling close to the speed of light
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.91,0:24:38.45,English1,,0,0,0,,is kind of an elixir of life
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.48,0:24:41.45,English1,,0,0,0,,because your biological clock slows down
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.49,0:24:43.62,English1,,0,0,0,,relative to those you leave behind.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.65,0:24:46.29,English1,,0,0,0,,This phenomenon may provide us humans,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.32,0:24:48.36,English1,,0,0,0,,who only live for a century or so,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.39,0:24:50.79,English1,,0,0,0,,a practical means to travel to the stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.83,0:24:52.96,English1,,0,0,0,,where the magic show of spacetime
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.00,0:24:55.40,English1,,0,0,0,,really gets crazy.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.36,0:25:07.26,English1,,0,0,0,,The 19th-century astronomer William Herschel
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.29,0:25:09.56,English1,,0,0,0,,loved to share the wonders of the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.60,0:25:11.60,English1,,0,0,0,,with his son John.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.44,0:25:25.84,English1,,0,0,0,,I once had a friend, very clever fellow,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.88,0:25:28.01,English1,,0,0,0,,an astronomer and a parson at Leeds,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.05,0:25:30.75,English1,,0,0,0,,by the name of John Michell.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:30.78,0:25:33.35,English1,,0,0,0,,Poor man died when you were a babe,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.39,0:25:35.29,English1,,0,0,0,,God rest his soul.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.32,0:25:37.36,English1,,0,0,0,,He held that some stars
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.39,0:25:39.36,English1,,0,0,0,,are invisible.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.39,0:25:42.69,English1,,0,0,0,,They really exist,\Nbut we shall never see them.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.73,0:25:46.06,English1,,0,0,0,,"Dark stars," Michell called them.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.83,0:25:49.93,English1,,0,0,0,,With all due respect, Father,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.97,0:25:52.54,English1,,0,0,0,,surely your friend was mistaken.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.57,0:25:54.21,English1,,0,0,0,,If no one can see them,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.24,0:25:57.01,English1,,0,0,0,,then how can we possibly know they exist?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.58,0:26:01.91,English1,,0,0,0,,Did you see the man\Nwho left those footprints, John?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.08,0:26:04.55,English1,,0,0,0,,Why, no, Father.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.58,0:26:05.55,English1,,0,0,0,,I did not.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.58,0:26:08.42,English1,,0,0,0,,But do you know that he exists?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.44,0:26:28.31,English1,,0,0,0,,John Michell is one of the greatest scientists
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.34,0:26:30.68,English1,,0,0,0,,you've probably never heard of.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.71,0:26:33.31,English1,,0,0,0,,He lived and worked in England in the 18th century.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.35,0:26:37.02,English1,,0,0,0,,If he ever sat for a portrait, it no longer exists.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.05,0:26:39.52,English1,,0,0,0,,He was once described by an acquaintance
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.55,0:26:41.19,English1,,0,0,0,,as "a short little man,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.22,0:26:44.76,English1,,0,0,0,,of black complexion, and fat."
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.79,0:26:47.53,English1,,0,0,0,,Michell imagined a star so big,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.56,0:26:51.03,English1,,0,0,0,,so massive, that nothing, not even light,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.06,0:26:53.60,English1,,0,0,0,,could escape its gravitational grip.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.63,0:26:55.53,English1,,0,0,0,,Can you find the dark star?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.57,0:26:58.44,English1,,0,0,0,,You can't see it with your eyes, not directly,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.47,0:27:00.94,English1,,0,0,0,,but it may leave a kind of footprint
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.97,0:27:02.94,English1,,0,0,0,,on the cosmic shore.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.98,0:27:05.38,English1,,0,0,0,,Michell realized that we might be able to detect
Dialogue: 0,0:27:05.41,0:27:08.78,English1,,0,0,0,,some of these dark stars because of their extreme gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.81,0:27:10.18,English1,,0,0,0,,If one happened to be near
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.22,0:27:12.45,English1,,0,0,0,,a smaller, luminous companion star,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.49,0:27:15.52,English1,,0,0,0,,that star would appear to travel in a tight orbit
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.55,0:27:18.39,English1,,0,0,0,,around nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:18.42,0:27:19.89,English1,,0,0,0,,Even though we can't see it,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.93,0:27:21.63,English1,,0,0,0,,we know something with a lot of mass
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.66,0:27:23.29,English1,,0,0,0,,has to be right there.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.33,0:27:24.80,English1,,0,0,0,,A dark star,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.83,0:27:28.07,English1,,0,0,0,,or what today we call a black hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.77,0:27:31.47,English1,,0,0,0,,What does a black hole look like
Dialogue: 0,0:27:31.50,0:27:33.64,English1,,0,0,0,,and what would it be like inside?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.67,0:27:35.97,English1,,0,0,0,,We'll get there, but first,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.01,0:27:39.31,English1,,0,0,0,,let's make a pit stop in my hometown,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.35,0:27:41.55,English1,,0,0,0,,New York City,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.58,0:27:42.91,English1,,0,0,0,,where it's always seemed to me
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.95,0:27:45.98,English1,,0,0,0,,that everything is in constant motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.02,0:27:48.72,English1,,0,0,0,,I've lived here most of my life.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.75,0:27:50.82,English1,,0,0,0,,There's always something new to see.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.86,0:27:53.66,English1,,0,0,0,,But one thing never changes-- gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.69,0:27:55.73,English1,,0,0,0,,Gravity on Earth has been the same
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.76,0:27:58.16,English1,,0,0,0,,for the past four and a half billion years.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.20,0:28:01.33,English1,,0,0,0,,But what if, today, we could alter it?
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.37,0:28:03.17,English1,,0,0,0,,Gravity is a distortion
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.20,0:28:05.17,English1,,0,0,0,,in the shape of spacetime
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.20,0:28:07.17,English1,,0,0,0,,as Einstein showed.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.21,0:28:09.07,English1,,0,0,0,,Space can expand and contract
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.11,0:28:10.54,English1,,0,0,0,,and warp without limit.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.22,0:28:18.52,English1,,0,0,0,,If the Earth's size or density
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.55,0:28:20.02,English1,,0,0,0,,were even a little different,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.05,0:28:21.85,English1,,0,0,0,,its gravity would be, too.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:21.89,0:28:23.92,English1,,0,0,0,,There's an infinite range of possibilities.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:23.96,0:28:25.79,English1,,0,0,0,,New Yorkers feel right at home
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.83,0:28:27.36,English1,,0,0,0,,in the gravitational pull of the Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:27.39,0:28:29.89,English1,,0,0,0,,called "one g."
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.80,0:28:38.17,English1,,0,0,0,,Suppose we turn off the gravity on one of its streets.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.58,0:28:46.48,English1,,0,0,0,,People and objects that were already in motion
Dialogue: 0,0:28:46.51,0:28:48.65,English1,,0,0,0,,are launched into flight.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.69,0:29:00.06,English1,,0,0,0,,Now what if I turn the gravity up
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.09,0:29:02.63,English1,,0,0,0,,to, say, eight or nine g's?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:02.66,0:29:04.16,English1,,0,0,0,,Out of compassion,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.20,0:29:06.66,English1,,0,0,0,,let's evacuate the area.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.83,0:29:09.57,English1,,0,0,0,,This is about the same g-force
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.60,0:29:12.34,English1,,0,0,0,,that a fighter pilot in a high-speed turn would feel.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:12.37,0:29:14.14,English1,,0,0,0,,A few minutes of this wouldn't hurt you,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.17,0:29:16.74,English1,,0,0,0,,but it wouldn't be comfortable.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:16.78,0:29:19.41,English1,,0,0,0,,At 100,000 g's,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.45,0:29:21.35,English1,,0,0,0,,even fire hydrants become crushed
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.38,0:29:23.98,English1,,0,0,0,,by their own enormous weight.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.02,0:29:25.75,English1,,0,0,0,,But at millions of g's,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.79,0:29:28.49,English1,,0,0,0,,even light bows to gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.52,0:29:31.09,English1,,0,0,0,,The light still moves at its constant speed,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.12,0:29:33.12,English1,,0,0,0,,but it cannot escape.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.13,0:29:36.36,English1,,0,0,0,,Michell's dark star...
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.40,0:29:38.60,English1,,0,0,0,,our black hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:38.63,0:29:42.20,English1,,0,0,0,,And the nearest one may be closer than you think.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.01,0:29:52.58,English1,,0,0,0,,Not every star can become a black hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.61,0:29:55.62,English1,,0,0,0,,Only about one in a thousand is massive enough.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.66,0:29:58.93,English1,,0,0,0,,The nearest one could be within 100 light years of Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.97,0:30:03.23,English1,,0,0,0,,Black holes aren't the mythic cosmic\Nvacuum cleaners of science fiction.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.26,0:30:06.07,English1,,0,0,0,,They don't go around gobbling up\Nunsuspecting worlds.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.10,0:30:07.90,English1,,0,0,0,,You've got to come to them.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.94,0:30:09.50,English1,,0,0,0,,But if you do,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.54,0:30:12.07,English1,,0,0,0,,it might be the last thing you ever see.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.14,0:30:18.85,English1,,0,0,0,,That was us resisting a few million g's of gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:18.88,0:30:22.28,English1,,0,0,0,,Don't forget, that thing swallows light.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.32,0:30:24.32,English1,,0,0,0,,We'll keep our distance.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.66,0:30:30.46,English1,,0,0,0,,When giant stars exhaust their nuclear fuel,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.49,0:30:32.13,English1,,0,0,0,,they can no longer stay hot enough
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.16,0:30:34.93,English1,,0,0,0,,to fend off the inward pull of their own gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:34.96,0:30:38.70,English1,,0,0,0,,The most massive stars collapse into darkness,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:38.73,0:30:40.87,English1,,0,0,0,,leaving only their gravity behind.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.90,0:30:44.37,English1,,0,0,0,,This black hole enshrouds\N{\i1}the shrunken corpse
Dialogue: 0,0:30:44.41,0:30:46.14,English1,,0,0,0,,of a supergiant star.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.17,0:30:48.28,English1,,0,0,0,,The star itself has shriveled into something
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.31,0:30:50.48,English1,,0,0,0,,even smaller than this darkness,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:50.51,0:30:53.65,English1,,0,0,0,,only 64 kilometers wide.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.52,0:30:58.72,English1,,0,0,0,,This is the first black hole ever discovered--
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.75,0:31:00.99,English1,,0,0,0,,Cygnus X-1.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.02,0:31:03.39,English1,,0,0,0,,How did we on Earth ever find something
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.42,0:31:06.46,English1,,0,0,0,,so small and dark and far away?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.49,0:31:11.80,English1,,0,0,0,,We looked at it in another kind of light. X-rays.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.83,0:31:14.57,English1,,0,0,0,,In X-ray light, we lost sight of the blue star
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.60,0:31:18.24,English1,,0,0,0,,because its surface is a tepid 30,000 degrees.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.27,0:31:20.84,English1,,0,0,0,,But the disk of gas around the black hole
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.88,0:31:25.68,English1,,0,0,0,,glowed brilliantly in X-rays at 100 million degrees.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.71,0:31:27.51,English1,,0,0,0,,As William Herschel discovered,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.55,0:31:32.25,English1,,0,0,0,,many stars have close companions\Nforming a binary star system.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:32.29,0:31:34.52,English1,,0,0,0,,But if one member of such a pair is enormous
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.56,0:31:36.49,English1,,0,0,0,,and the other is compact,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.52,0:31:39.99,English1,,0,0,0,,the smaller star can drain\Nand consume the atmosphere
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.03,0:31:42.43,English1,,0,0,0,,of its larger sibling.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:42.46,0:31:46.70,English1,,0,0,0,,This neurotic relationship\Ncan last for millions of years.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:46.73,0:31:50.70,English1,,0,0,0,,The atmosphere of the larger star was being siphoned onto
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.74,0:31:53.54,English1,,0,0,0,,a glowing hot accretion disk that revolves around
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.57,0:31:56.61,English1,,0,0,0,,and spirals into a black hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.64,0:32:00.21,English1,,0,0,0,,The overwhelming gravity was\Naccelerating the blue star's gas
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.25,0:32:01.68,English1,,0,0,0,,into a death spiral,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:01.72,0:32:04.45,English1,,0,0,0,,crossing the spacetime boundary,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:04.49,0:32:06.05,English1,,0,0,0,,never to be seen again.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.09,0:32:09.52,English1,,0,0,0,,The fateful boundary that separates a black hole
Dialogue: 0,0:32:09.56,0:32:13.03,English1,,0,0,0,,from the rest of the universe is called an event horizon.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.06,0:32:15.90,English1,,0,0,0,,From our point of view, the substance in the disk
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.93,0:32:18.23,English1,,0,0,0,,slows down as it approaches the event horizon,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:18.27,0:32:20.70,English1,,0,0,0,,never quite reaching it.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:20.74,0:32:23.30,English1,,0,0,0,,But if you were riding on that spiraling gas--
Dialogue: 0,0:32:23.34,0:32:25.14,English1,,0,0,0,,and I don't advise it--
Dialogue: 0,0:32:25.17,0:32:28.14,English1,,0,0,0,,you would sail past the event horizon in a matter of seconds
Dialogue: 0,0:32:28.18,0:32:33.18,English1,,0,0,0,,into the undiscovered country from which no traveler returns.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:42.36,0:32:45.23,English1,,0,0,0,,We have searched the hearts of dozens of galaxies,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.26,0:32:49.40,English1,,0,0,0,,and in every case, we have found\Na super-massive black hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.43,0:32:53.83,English1,,0,0,0,,Our own galaxy is no exception.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:53.87,0:32:57.77,English1,,0,0,0,,The stars nearest the center\N{\i1}of our galaxy whip around
Dialogue: 0,0:32:57.81,0:33:00.47,English1,,0,0,0,,at more than 40 million kilometers an hour.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.04,0:33:05.85,English1,,0,0,0,,What could make them move so fast?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:05.88,0:33:07.58,English1,,0,0,0,,The only logical explanation
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.62,0:33:09.95,English1,,0,0,0,,is that something with the mass
Dialogue: 0,0:33:09.98,0:33:14.45,English1,,0,0,0,,of four million suns lies at the center.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.49,0:33:17.96,English1,,0,0,0,,So where's the blazing light of four million suns?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.99,0:33:19.43,English1,,0,0,0,,Since we can't see it,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:19.46,0:33:22.23,English1,,0,0,0,,it must be imprisoned inside a black hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.67,0:33:31.87,English1,,0,0,0,,Earth is far enough away to be perfectly safe.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:31.91,0:33:35.08,English1,,0,0,0,,Other worlds might not be so lucky.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:37.41,0:33:40.05,English1,,0,0,0,,If you somehow survived the perilous journey
Dialogue: 0,0:33:40.08,0:33:41.88,English1,,0,0,0,,across the event horizon,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.92,0:33:43.45,English1,,0,0,0,,you'd be able to look back out
Dialogue: 0,0:33:43.48,0:33:46.45,English1,,0,0,0,,and see the entire future history of the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.49,0:33:48.49,English1,,0,0,0,,unfold before your eyes.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.53,0:33:53.06,English1,,0,0,0,,How?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:53.09,0:33:54.83,English1,,0,0,0,,Because when spacetime is warped
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.86,0:33:57.23,English1,,0,0,0,,by the extreme gravity of a black hole,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:57.27,0:34:00.00,English1,,0,0,0,,time is stretched to the limit.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.60,0:34:05.91,English1,,0,0,0,,But what would be in front of you?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.94,0:34:08.58,English1,,0,0,0,,Before we go there, I should warn you
Dialogue: 0,0:34:08.61,0:34:11.41,English1,,0,0,0,,that we're entering uncharted scientific territory.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.45,0:34:15.35,English1,,0,0,0,,For all we know, there may be\Nundiscovered laws of physics
Dialogue: 0,0:34:15.38,0:34:17.95,English1,,0,0,0,,that govern events at the center of a black hole.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:20.12,0:34:22.52,English1,,0,0,0,,But until the next Einstein comes along,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.56,0:34:25.13,English1,,0,0,0,,let's perform a thought experiment.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.53,0:34:29.76,English1,,0,0,0,,That's how John Michell first imagined dark stars
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.80,0:34:31.93,English1,,0,0,0,,in the 18th century,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.97,0:34:35.30,English1,,0,0,0,,and how Einstein conceived of his theory of rela...
Dialogue: 0,0:35:27.37,0:35:30.77,English1,,0,0,0,,Father, do you believe in ghosts?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.81,0:35:34.01,English1,,0,0,0,,Oh, no, not in the human kind of ghosts.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.05,0:35:35.61,English1,,0,0,0,,No, not at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.65,0:35:38.78,English1,,0,0,0,,But look up, my boy,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.82,0:35:41.89,English1,,0,0,0,,and see a sky full of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:44.09,0:35:47.12,English1,,0,0,0,,If you could survive the trip into a black hole,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:47.16,0:35:48.69,English1,,0,0,0,,you might emerge in another place
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.73,0:35:51.20,English1,,0,0,0,,and time in our own universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:51.23,0:35:54.36,English1,,0,0,0,,circumventing the first commandment of relativity...
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.40,0:35:57.33,English1,,0,0,0,,thou shalt not travel faster than light.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.00,0:36:02.24,English1,,0,0,0,,Nothing can move through space faster than light.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.27,0:36:04.71,English1,,0,0,0,,But space is not mere emptiness.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.74,0:36:09.31,English1,,0,0,0,,Its properties can stretch\N{\i1}and shrink and can be deformed.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:09.35,0:36:13.58,English1,,0,0,0,,And when that happens, time is deformed, too.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.75,0:36:20.49,English1,,0,0,0,,Einstein discovered that spaceand time are just two aspects
Dialogue: 0,0:36:20.53,0:36:23.73,English1,,0,0,0,,of the same thing, spacetime.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:23.76,0:36:26.33,English1,,0,0,0,,Spacetime itself can deform enough
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.36,0:36:29.67,English1,,0,0,0,,to carry you anywhere at any speed.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.70,0:36:33.64,English1,,0,0,0,,Black holes may very well be tunnels\Nthrough the universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.49,0:36:52.26,English1,,0,0,0,,On this intergalactic subway\N{\i1}system, you could travel
Dialogue: 0,0:36:52.29,0:36:54.36,English1,,0,0,0,,to the farthest reaches of spacetime,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:54.39,0:36:57.80,English1,,0,0,0,,or you might arrive in someplace even more amazing.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:00.40,0:37:03.87,English1,,0,0,0,,We might find ourselves in an\Naltogether different universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:03.90,0:37:06.70,English1,,0,0,0,,But how can a whole universe fit\Ninside of a black hole,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.74,0:37:11.44,English1,,0,0,0,,which is only a small part of our universe?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:11.48,0:37:14.55,English1,,0,0,0,,It's another magic trick of spacetime.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:14.58,0:37:17.48,English1,,0,0,0,,The phenomenal gravity of a black hole
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.52,0:37:21.59,English1,,0,0,0,,can warp the space of an entire universe inside it.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.76,0:37:32.13,English1,,0,0,0,,Our local gravity might be a drag to us,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.16,0:37:33.83,English1,,0,0,0,,but it's really feeble compared
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.87,0:37:36.30,English1,,0,0,0,,with what goes on inside a collapsed star.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:36.33,0:37:38.40,English1,,0,0,0,,As far as we know,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:38.44,0:37:42.14,English1,,0,0,0,,when a giant star collapses\N{\i1}to make a black hole,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.17,0:37:43.91,English1,,0,0,0,,the extreme density and pressure at the center
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.94,0:37:48.68,English1,,0,0,0,,mimic the Big Bang, which gave rise to our universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:48.71,0:37:50.41,English1,,0,0,0,,And a universe inside a black hole
Dialogue: 0,0:37:50.45,0:37:52.98,English1,,0,0,0,,might give rise to its own black holes.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:53.02,0:37:55.55,English1,,0,0,0,,And those could lead to other universes.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.79,0:38:03.69,English1,,0,0,0,,Maybe that's how our cosmos came to be.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.37,0:38:17.17,English1,,0,0,0,,For all we know,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.21,0:38:21.45,English1,,0,0,0,,if you want to see what it's like inside a black hole,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.48,0:38:23.75,English1,,0,0,0,,just look around you.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.39,0:38:31.02,English1,,0,0,0,,William Herschel went on to discover that the sun
Dialogue: 0,0:38:31.06,0:38:34.53,English1,,0,0,0,,and its planets are moving through the Milky Way.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:34.56,0:38:37.13,English1,,0,0,0,,And whatever became of his son John?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.16,0:38:40.13,English1,,0,0,0,,He grew up to become a great scientist.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.17,0:38:43.80,English1,,0,0,0,,His deep-space observations built on those of his father
Dialogue: 0,0:38:43.84,0:38:46.47,English1,,0,0,0,,to become the basis for the standard catalog of galaxies
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.50,0:38:48.41,English1,,0,0,0,,we use today.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.44,0:38:51.64,English1,,0,0,0,,When William was in failing health, John stayed with him
Dialogue: 0,0:38:51.68,0:38:53.64,English1,,0,0,0,,through the long nights at his telescope
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.68,0:38:55.48,English1,,0,0,0,,to help him sweep the stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.51,0:39:00.48,English1,,0,0,0,,And when his father died, John wrote his epitaph...
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.52,0:39:03.85,English1,,0,0,0,,"He broke through the walls of heaven."
Dialogue: 0,0:39:15.20,0:39:16.83,English1,,0,0,0,,John often reminisced
Dialogue: 0,0:39:16.87,0:39:18.90,English1,,0,0,0,,about those summer nights with his father.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:18.94,0:39:23.54,English1,,0,0,0,,Maybe that's why he sought a way to preserve the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:25.11,0:39:26.84,English1,,0,0,0,,John Herschel was one of the founders
Dialogue: 0,0:39:26.88,0:39:28.91,English1,,0,0,0,,of a new form of time travel,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:28.95,0:39:32.78,English1,,0,0,0,,a means to capture light and memories.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.82,0:39:35.25,English1,,0,0,0,,He actually coined a word for it,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:35.29,0:39:37.72,English1,,0,0,0,,photography.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.56,0:39:44.09,English1,,0,0,0,,When you think about it,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.13,0:39:46.93,English1,,0,0,0,,photography is a form of time travel.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:46.97,0:39:50.43,English1,,0,0,0,,This man is staring at us from across the centuries...
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.47,0:39:52.87,English1,,0,0,0,,a ghost preserved by light.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:52.90,0:39:55.71,English1,,0,0,0,,It's not hard to imagine that in the near future,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:55.74,0:39:57.47,English1,,0,0,0,,we'll be able to capture the past
Dialogue: 0,0:39:57.51,0:39:59.71,English1,,0,0,0,,in all three dimensions.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:59.74,0:40:03.08,English1,,0,0,0,,We'll be able to step inside a memory.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.82,0:40:10.62,English1,,0,0,0,,It may not be possible to travel backward in time,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:10.66,0:40:14.59,English1,,0,0,0,,but perhaps, one day, we can bring the past to us.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.19,0:40:19.40,English1,,0,0,0,,Here's a moment from my past.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.43,0:40:20.90,English1,,0,0,0,,Like John Herschel,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:20.93,0:40:23.73,English1,,0,0,0,,I'm remembering a younger version of myself.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:23.77,0:40:26.34,English1,,0,0,0,,December 20, 1975.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:26.37,0:40:28.84,English1,,0,0,0,,A snowy day in Ithaca, New York.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:28.87,0:40:32.14,English1,,0,0,0,,A branchpoint on the road that brought me
Dialogue: 0,0:40:32.18,0:40:35.08,English1,,0,0,0,,to this moment with you.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.11,0:40:37.88,English1,,0,0,0,,It was the day I met Carl Sagan.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.72,0:40:44.52,English1,,0,0,0,,Reminds me of those ghost stars in the sky...
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.46,0:40:53.09,English1,,0,0,0,,you know, the ones that still shine their light upon us\Nlong after they're gone.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.30,0:00:06.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,眼见并不为实
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.91,0:00:09.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们的感官会误导我们
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.31,0:00:12.11,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这些星星并不是我们看到的样子
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.15,0:00:14.61,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}通过科学展示出的宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.65,0:00:17.95,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}比我们所能想象的更离奇
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.98,0:00:22.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}光 时间 空间 万有引力
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.49,0:00:24.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}共同创造出
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.49,0:00:27.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们从未体验过的现实
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.03,0:00:30.03,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}让我们一探究竟
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.10,0:00:32.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}跟我来
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.00,0:00:38.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1802年 像这样的一个夜晚
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.17,0:00:41.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,天文学家威廉·赫歇尔和他的儿子
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.34,0:00:43.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在英国海边散步
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.94,0:00:46.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,赫歇尔（恒星天文学之父）是有史以来第一位
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.85,0:00:49.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,看穿宇宙深层奥秘的人
Dialogue: 0,0:00:51.95,0:00:54.15,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他看穿了光线和时间
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.19,0:00:56.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}一起变出的戏法
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.06,0:00:57.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,父亲
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.96,0:01:00.03,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你相信有鬼魂吗
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.06,0:01:01.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,怎么了  我相信
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.90,0:01:04.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你信
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.46,0:01:05.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我真没想到
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.97,0:01:09.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,哦,不,不是人死后的鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.70,0:01:11.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,绝不是那种
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.47,0:01:13.94,Chinese,,0,0,0,,抬头看 儿子
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.97,0:01:16.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,天空中满是鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.81,0:01:18.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,星星  父亲
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.91,0:01:20.51,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我没听懂
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.55,0:01:25.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,每个星星都像我们的太阳那么亮 那么大
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.42,0:01:29.72,Chinese,,0,0,0,,想想看要把太阳移到多远以外
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.76,0:01:33.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,才能让它看上去像星星那样小
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.43,0:01:37.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,星星发出的光 速度很快
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.23,0:01:38.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最快的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.73,0:01:41.37,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但并不是无限的快
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.40,0:01:45.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,星光到达我们这里需要时间
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.24,0:01:48.37,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最近的可能需要几年
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.41,0:01:50.98,Chinese,,0,0,0,,其他那些  几百年
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.01,0:01:53.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还有一些特别远的
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.51,0:01:57.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,需要亿万年才能到达地球
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.58,0:02:02.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,等那些星星发出的光到达这里
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.26,0:02:04.72,Chinese,,0,0,0,,星星已经死了
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.76,0:02:09.33,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对这些星星来说  我们看到的只是它们的鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.36,0:02:11.66,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们看到它们的光
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.70,0:02:15.10,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但它们的星球已经死了很久很久
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.70,0:02:20.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,约翰  我比我们的古人
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.77,0:02:22.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,能看到更古老的过去
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.88,0:02:25.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,几百万年前的过去
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.22,0:02:31.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}威廉·赫歇尔是第一个认识到
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.22,0:02:33.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}望远镜就是一个时间机器
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.89,0:02:36.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们看向太空
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.39,0:02:38.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}就是看向过去
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.66,0:02:44.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}一秒钟  光穿越30万公里
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.97,0:02:47.77,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}或者18万6千英里
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.80,0:02:50.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}几乎就是地球到月亮的距离
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.24,0:02:54.11,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}所以月亮离我们1光秒
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.14,0:02:56.04,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}下次你看向月亮
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.08,0:02:59.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}你就会看到1秒钟以前的过去
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.25,0:04:41.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,太阳
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.88,0:04:43.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}并不真的在那个位置
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.62,0:04:45.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}太阳实际上升出地平线
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.59,0:04:48.05,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}是两分钟以后的事情
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.09,0:04:50.42,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}日出只是个幻象
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.46,0:04:53.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}大气层使射入的阳光发生了折射
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.26,0:04:55.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}就像镜片和一杯水那样
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.76,0:04:59.40,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}所以我们看到的只是地平线之上的投影
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.43,0:05:01.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}太阳本身还没到达那个位置
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.27,0:05:05.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我身后的太阳只是海市蜃楼
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.94,0:05:08.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就像那闪烁的图像
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.04,0:05:09.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,漂浮在
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.21,0:05:12.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,炎热天气下的沙漠远方
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.28,0:05:15.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,日光需要8分钟才能达到地球
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.28,0:05:18.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,太阳离我们8光分
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.55,0:05:21.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对于太阳来说  我们只能看到它
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.32,0:05:22.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,8分钟之前的样子
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.23,0:05:26.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还有一件事
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.63,0:05:28.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,太阳并不是真的 升起
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.90,0:05:31.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球带着我们一起旋转
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.63,0:05:35.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,看上去也许不像  但是这个时候
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.57,0:05:37.94,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我比飞机走的还快
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.97,0:05:40.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你也是  其他所有人都一样
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.47,0:05:41.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当我看过去
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.68,0:05:42.94,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地平线
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.98,0:05:44.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并不真的存在
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.48,0:05:46.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,根本没有边缘
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.81,0:05:49.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地平线也是一种幻象
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.33,0:06:06.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球离
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.93,0:06:09.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最外围的行星  海王星的距离
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.04,0:06:11.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,随着环日轨道而不同
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.54,0:06:15.11,Chinese,,0,0,0,,平均来说  光要4个小时才能传来
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.14,0:06:16.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以对我们来说
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.78,0:06:20.65,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们看到的是4小时前海王星的样子
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.68,0:06:23.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,距离 4光时
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.35,0:06:24.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但行星间的距离
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.62,0:06:26.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就算最遥远的
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.29,0:06:28.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也只不过是微不足道的
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.02,0:06:31.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,相对星系间和恒星间的距离来说
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.86,0:06:39.33,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}一旦我们离开太阳系
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.37,0:06:41.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们就需要把距离单位
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.20,0:06:44.34,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从光时换到光年
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.37,0:06:46.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光年是宇宙中的距离单位
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.91,0:06:50.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1光年将近10万亿公里
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.04,0:06:52.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大约6万亿英里
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.71,0:06:55.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙距离单位中  就像1米或1英里那样
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.92,0:06:58.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它是光线用1年时间可以穿越的距离长度
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.22,0:07:02.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}离太阳最近的恒星  比邻星
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.06,0:07:05.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}离地球的距离超过4光年一点点
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.43,0:07:07.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}4光年有多远
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.66,0:07:10.03,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}NASA（美国国家航空航天局）的旅行者探测器
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.06,0:07:13.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}速度超过每小时5万6千公里
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.00,0:07:17.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}就算这么惊人的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.17,0:07:21.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}也需要超过8万年  才能到达最近的恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.85,0:07:26.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}昂宿星团（昴日星官大公鸡）的恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.85,0:07:28.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}距离我们 400光年
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.25,0:07:31.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}想象之舟
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.95,0:07:34.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}有着一种不同寻常的能力
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.25,0:07:35.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}独一无二的
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.96,0:07:39.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它能让我们看到
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.29,0:07:43.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光从遥远的恒星或星系发出
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.26,0:07:45.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,直到地球的情形
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.63,0:07:49.57,Chinese,,0,0,0,,♪ ♪
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.60,0:07:53.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}400年前  光从昴宿星团出发时
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.11,0:07:56.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}伽利略首次使用望远镜
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.81,0:07:59.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}几年后 他尝试测算光的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.45,0:08:01.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但是没有成功
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.28,0:08:04.12,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他的计划很高明  可惜当时的科技
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.15,0:08:07.12,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}还不能测量那么快的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.15,0:08:09.66,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}像光那么快的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.79,0:08:14.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们从地球上观察蟹状星云时
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.13,0:08:17.10,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们看到的是更古老的过去
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.13,0:08:19.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}蟹状星云曾是一颗巨大的恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.63,0:08:22.10,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}质量比太阳大10倍
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.14,0:08:24.94,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}爆炸成为一颗超新星
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.97,0:08:26.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}它的中心是颗脉冲星
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.01,0:08:29.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}城市般大小的一颗坍塌星 （中子星）
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.48,0:08:31.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}每秒自转30次
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.02,0:08:42.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,脉冲星的螺旋磁场
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.49,0:08:44.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,疯狂地卷动 周围的电子
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.59,0:08:48.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,将它们加速到接近光的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.66,0:08:52.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们发出蓝色的光芒照亮超新星爆炸时
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.17,0:08:54.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,产生的气态卷须
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.67,0:08:56.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}蟹状星云
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.20,0:08:59.34,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}距离地球大约6500光年
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.01,0:09:03.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在某些宗教信仰中
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.04,0:09:05.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}那是整个宇宙的年纪
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.51,0:09:09.15,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但如果宇宙只有6500岁
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.18,0:09:12.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们怎么可能看到更远的光
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.29,0:09:14.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}比蟹状星云还远的光
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.12,0:09:16.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}做不到
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.12,0:09:17.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}那并没有足够的时间
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.03,0:09:20.66,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}让光从距离
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.69,0:09:24.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}超过6500光年的地方传来地球
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.53,0:09:27.10,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}那点时间只够光在
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.13,0:09:30.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们的银河系中穿越很短的距离
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.00,0:09:32.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果相信宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.24,0:09:35.04,Chinese,,0,0,0,,只有6千到7千岁
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.08,0:09:38.11,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是熄灭了银河系中大部分的光
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.15,0:09:41.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,更别提那些可观测宇宙中
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.21,0:09:44.72,Chinese,,0,0,0,,上千亿星系发出的光
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.28,0:10:16.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们银河系的中心
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.42,0:10:19.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}距离地球大约3万光年
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.62,0:10:21.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们今天看到的光
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.59,0:10:25.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}从银河系的核心出发时
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.09,0:10:26.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的远古祖先找到了
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.03,0:10:29.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,超越死亡的方法
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.70,0:10:35.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}使用绘画的力量
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.70,0:10:38.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}给予后世启示
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.77,0:10:40.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,♪ ♪
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.71,0:10:50.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}从草帽星系传来的光
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.38,0:10:53.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}走了3千万年
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.82,0:10:57.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当光发出来时  我们的祖先还住在树上
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.29,0:11:01.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们大约5公斤重  还有长长的尾巴
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.46,0:11:03.96,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但就算离我们3千万光年之外
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.00,0:11:08.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从宇宙中看 也不过就在我们的后院
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.80,0:11:14.11,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}那个星系属于后发座星系团
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.14,0:11:17.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}3亿2千万光年之遥
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.41,0:11:19.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}当这里的光出发时
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.31,0:11:22.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}当时的地球又是怎样的呢
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.32,0:11:27.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,没有我们熟悉的大陆  海洋  河流
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.59,0:11:31.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的远古祖先刚刚从水中登上陆地
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.83,0:11:33.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,很古老的光
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.66,0:11:36.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但远不是 我们能看到的 最古老的光
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.87,0:11:42.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最古老的光已经很微弱了
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.10,0:11:44.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}暗夜中虚弱的鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.27,0:11:47.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}看到圆圈中的红点吗
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.34,0:11:50.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}那是我们能见的最古老星系之一
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.84,0:11:55.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}你看到的是134亿岁高龄的星光
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.88,0:11:59.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}通过哈勃太空望远镜捕捉到的
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.63,0:12:10.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它来自第一代的星星
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.46,0:12:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当时的地球什么情况
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.03,0:12:15.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,完全没情况
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.20,0:12:18.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当时 没有地球 没有太阳 没有银河系
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.87,0:12:22.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们都是几十亿后才诞生的
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.88,0:12:27.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当我们看向宇宙的更深处
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.88,0:12:31.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,好像已经到了宇宙的尽头
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.22,0:12:35.05,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但 事实上
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.09,0:12:37.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是时间的开始
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.84,0:12:45.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球向下拉着我们
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.44,0:12:48.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们不断地反抗引力
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.93,0:13:05.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这个小女孩用尽全力要爬出
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.26,0:13:07.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}引力的包围
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.53,0:13:11.40,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}从第一次尝试站立到最后的倒下
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.44,0:13:14.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们努力克服地心引力
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.94,0:13:19.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们在重力场中诞生  生活  过世
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.88,0:13:24.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}重力场几乎和宇宙本身一样的古老
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.32,0:13:26.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}有多古老
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.95,0:13:30.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}为了想象宇宙的138亿年岁月
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.56,0:13:32.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们把所有的宇宙时间
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.12,0:13:34.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}压缩在一份单张的年历中
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.63,0:13:39.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}现在就是12月31号的午夜
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.46,0:13:43.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}1月1号就是时间的开始
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.50,0:13:45.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,看到那耀眼的烟雾吗
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.90,0:13:49.04,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它是大爆炸遗留下的辐射物
Dialogue: 0,0:13:49.07,0:13:51.04,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大爆炸创造了宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.08,0:13:54.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,138亿年前
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.41,0:14:00.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在我们站在已知空间和时间的边缘
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.09,0:14:04.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大爆炸之前是什么样子
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.32,0:14:05.96,Chinese,,0,0,0,,没人知道
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.99,0:14:08.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,没有丝毫 关于那之前的证据
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.83,0:14:10.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们有一些很疯狂的猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.66,0:14:12.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是关于宇宙的来源
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.16,0:14:15.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们以后会提到
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.17,0:14:18.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们在宇宙的什么位置
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.10,0:14:21.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就在正中心
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.21,0:14:25.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在已知宇宙中 每个人都觉得自己很特殊
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.18,0:14:28.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}不论你身处哪个星系
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.05,0:14:31.15,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}当你看向宇宙时  你会发现自己
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.18,0:14:34.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}身处宇宙地平线的中心
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.52,0:14:36.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但这不过是个错觉
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.52,0:14:38.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,实际上  没有中心
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.39,0:14:40.83,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙地平线 和
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.86,0:14:43.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,海上的地平线 一样不真实
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.73,0:14:47.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是因为在 有起始时间的宇宙中
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.57,0:14:50.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光速是有限的
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.87,0:14:56.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大爆炸后的几亿年
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.88,0:15:00.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大量的氢气和氦气云团
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.05,0:15:03.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,凝结成最初的恒星和星系
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.32,0:15:04.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有了这些新的光源
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.88,0:15:07.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙漫长的黑暗时代终结了
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.92,0:15:10.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,随着宇宙的不断膨胀
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.49,0:15:14.19,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙进化的规模变得更加宏大
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.23,0:15:16.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最初的星星死亡
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.56,0:15:19.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}它们将较重的元素散布在宇宙中
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.90,0:15:22.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}使得行星的形成 成为可能
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.57,0:15:25.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}最终 生命的形成
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.74,0:15:33.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大爆炸形成了物质和能量
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.28,0:15:34.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还有
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.75,0:15:37.21,Chinese,,0,0,0,,创造了空间和时间
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.25,0:15:39.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还有束缚所有物质的力量
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.58,0:15:41.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,包括 重力
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.12,0:15:43.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,牛顿发现了一个数学定律
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.52,0:15:45.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可以形容重力的运作机制
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.92,0:15:49.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他可以用它解释行星间的运动
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.26,0:15:51.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,100多年后
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.26,0:15:55.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,威廉·赫歇尔 意识到 那还不是全部
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.44,0:16:04.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,约翰 你能保守秘密吗
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.78,0:16:06.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可以 父亲
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.61,0:16:10.98,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我有了一个发现  还没告诉过任何人
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.45,0:16:15.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球上的地心引力
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.65,0:16:17.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,同样是牛顿发现的
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.62,0:16:19.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,将行星保持在轨道上的引力
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.56,0:16:21.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我发现
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.13,0:16:25.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也同样适用于 相隔遥远的恒星们
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.16,0:16:29.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,爹  你咋知道的
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.47,0:16:31.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你能找到狮子座吗
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.64,0:16:35.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在那
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.01,0:16:37.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,干得好
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.34,0:16:39.94,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你能找到
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.98,0:16:43.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,连接头部和身体的那颗星吗
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.32,0:16:44.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那个
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.65,0:16:47.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那其实是两颗星
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.02,0:16:51.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,靠的很近 看上去就像一颗
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.02,0:16:54.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我用望远镜观察了很久
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.66,0:16:56.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你出生很久前就开始了
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.00,0:17:01.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们非常缓慢的 围绕相互移动
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.93,0:17:06.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,远比行星绕恒星运动的慢
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.17,0:17:10.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们今晚看到的许多星星
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.84,0:17:12.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可能大部分
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.84,0:17:15.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,按照看不见的规律移动
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.45,0:17:20.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,万有引力这个大帝国统治着所有的星球
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.20,0:17:31.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1个世纪前
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.56,0:17:33.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}艾萨克·牛顿备受困扰
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.47,0:17:36.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他也找不到引力的作用机制
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.54,0:17:39.10,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}相距甚远的物体 如何相互影响
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.14,0:17:42.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}不用接触就相互影响
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.91,0:17:47.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这个他称之为 超距作用 的问题困扰着他
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.88,0:17:52.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}19世纪 迈克尔·法拉第（电学之父）发现
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.38,0:17:55.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们被不可见的力场包围
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.49,0:17:58.19,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这解释了引力的运作机制
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.22,0:18:00.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}苹果和地球 并没有发生接触
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.83,0:18:03.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但是它们之间的力场产生了接触
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.50,0:18:07.03,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他想象引力产生的线
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.07,0:18:10.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}从每一个物体 向太空中辐射
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.10,0:18:15.37,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}地球 月亮 太阳  所有的一切
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.41,0:18:18.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这就是那个困扰牛顿的问题
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.28,0:18:20.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}的答案
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.91,0:18:25.65,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}1985年 詹姆斯·克拉克·麦克斯韦
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.68,0:18:28.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}把法拉第关于电磁场的理论
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.29,0:18:31.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}转化成了数学公式
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.09,0:18:35.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他发现这些磁场 电场都以波的形式在空间中移动
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.13,0:18:37.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}当他计算它们的移动速度时
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.76,0:18:40.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}结果是 光的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.77,0:18:42.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们才发现了  宇宙这个大挂毯上的线
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.77,0:18:44.57,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们才发现了  宇宙这个大挂毯上的线
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.60,0:18:47.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但是我们还无法 看出丰富的图案
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.71,0:18:51.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}时间 光 空间 重力
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.78,0:18:53.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}阿尔伯特·爱因斯坦 在柏林
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.31,0:18:55.11,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}研究他的引力理论时
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.15,0:18:58.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}墙上挂了这3位前辈的头像
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.88,0:19:02.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他知道他的成就  建立在他们的基础上
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.25,0:19:05.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}多年前  少年时  他有过一个顿悟
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.26,0:19:08.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}如同前辈们的理论那般惊天动地
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.93,0:19:10.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}那年夏天
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.63,0:19:13.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他在意大利遐想时的顿悟
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.06,0:19:20.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}1895年的夏天
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.90,0:19:23.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他父亲在德国的生意失败
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.73,0:19:26.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,全家搬到了意大利北部
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.24,0:19:29.04,Chinese,,0,0,0,,小爱因斯坦喜欢在这些路上散步
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.07,0:19:31.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,让他的思维随意发散
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.91,0:19:35.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里有着某些永恒的东西
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.31,0:19:38.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,和爱因斯坦最初的遐想时相比
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.92,0:19:41.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,基本没什么变化
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.26,0:19:49.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一天 他想到了光
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.59,0:19:52.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还有光速
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.10,0:19:54.30,Chinese,,0,0,0,,日常生活中 我们总是测量物体
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.33,0:19:57.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,相对于其他物体的移动速度
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.00,0:19:59.61,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}假设其他物体没有移动
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.27,0:20:03.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}宇宙中的其他物体没有运动
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.37,0:20:07.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}比方说  我的速度大约每小时10公里
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.21,0:20:09.61,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}相对于地面而言
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.65,0:20:12.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但我之前提过  大地也在运动
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.72,0:20:17.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}地球的转速超过每小时1600公里
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.12,0:20:18.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在环日轨道上
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.89,0:20:21.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}速度超过每小时10万公里
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.73,0:20:24.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}并且太阳系在银河系中运行
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.13,0:20:27.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}每小时50万英里（实际90万公里）的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.20,0:20:29.37,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}银河系在宇宙中运行
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.40,0:20:32.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}速度将近每小时150万英里（实际216万公里）
Dialogue: 0,0:20:32.50,0:20:35.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}宇宙中没有不动的地方
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.67,0:20:38.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}一切都在运动
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.51,0:20:41.61,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对小爱因斯坦来说  也是很难想象出
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.65,0:20:43.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一个绝对的标准
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.75,0:20:47.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,用来衡量所有这些相对的运动
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.20,0:21:02.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是这本书
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.83,0:21:05.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,启发了少年爱因斯坦
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.87,0:21:10.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,给了他一本书  改变了这个世界
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.04,0:21:12.34,Chinese,,0,0,0,,某种程度上  改变了这个宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.38,0:21:15.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,看这里  第一页
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.95,0:21:17.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它描述了令人惊讶的
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.85,0:21:19.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,电流通过电线的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.62,0:21:22.19,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光穿过宇宙的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.22,0:21:25.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,爱因斯坦记得他小时候从这本书里学到的
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.86,0:21:29.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,或许 最初 就在这里
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.29,0:21:30.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,想象着这个世界将会如何
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.96,0:21:33.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果可以用光速运动
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.70,0:21:40.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}爱因斯坦越想
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.20,0:21:42.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}越觉得困惑
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.11,0:21:45.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}如果你想象以光速运动
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.44,0:21:49.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}各个方面都充满了矛盾
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.31,0:21:52.08,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}爱因斯坦惊讶的发现 如此众多的
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.12,0:21:54.12,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}即使是被最伟大的权威人士
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.15,0:21:56.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}无条件接受的真理
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.72,0:21:58.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}竟是大错特错
Dialogue: 0,0:21:59.96,0:22:02.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}以高速运动时
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.33,0:22:05.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,必须遵守一些特定的规则
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.30,0:22:08.03,Chinese,,0,0,0,,爱因斯坦称之为 相对性原理
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.07,0:22:10.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}想象刚才那位呼啸而过
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.77,0:22:12.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}骑摩托的年轻女士
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.24,0:22:13.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}想象她骑车穿行
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.74,0:22:16.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在宇宙中
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.77,0:22:19.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}从移动的物体上发出的光
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.41,0:22:21.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}不论物体是静止还是移动
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.41,0:22:24.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}速度都是一样的
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.32,0:22:27.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}她的速度并不会增加光的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.25,0:22:29.05,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}从她的摩托车发出的光
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.09,0:22:31.65,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}依然是光的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.29,0:22:35.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大自然的谕旨
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.09,0:22:38.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,汝不可超越光速
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.93,0:22:41.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,同样 没有物质
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.50,0:22:44.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,传播速度可以达到或者超过光速
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.10,0:22:46.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,物理上 没有什么可以阻止你
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.20,0:22:48.77,Chinese,,0,0,0,,随心所欲地接近光的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.81,0:22:52.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,99.9%的光速 没问题
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.48,0:22:54.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是无论你怎么努力
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.95,0:22:57.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,都无法得到 最后的那个百分点
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.45,0:23:00.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,以现实的逻辑一致性来说
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.28,0:23:02.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,必然存在一个宇宙速度极限
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.13,0:23:12.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,鞭子发出的声音是因为
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.63,0:23:14.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,鞭头的移动速度超过了声速
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.63,0:23:16.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,产生了冲击波
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.47,0:23:18.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在意大利乡村的  一个小小的音爆
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.67,0:23:23.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,打雷也是一样的道理
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.87,0:23:26.98,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还有超音速飞机掠过时的声音
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.01,0:23:29.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那为什么光速
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.35,0:23:31.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,比音速更难超越
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.52,0:23:34.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,答案是 不仅仅光速
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.25,0:23:36.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,比音速快100万倍
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.49,0:23:38.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也因为 这不仅是一个工程学问题
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.92,0:23:40.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}像建造首架超音速飞机那种
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.49,0:23:42.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}光障
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.89,0:23:44.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是自然的基本定律
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.83,0:23:46.66,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就像万有引力一样基本
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.70,0:23:49.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,爱因斯坦为这个世界设定了绝对的准则
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.00,0:23:52.04,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这给了宇宙运动中的
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.07,0:23:54.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}所有相对运动强有力的支持
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.77,0:23:56.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}光速就是那么快
Dialogue: 0,0:23:56.57,0:24:00.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,无论光源移动的快慢
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.74,0:24:04.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,相对其他任何东西 光速是恒定的
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.75,0:24:07.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,没有什么可以追上光
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.22,0:24:11.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,自然定律的伟大就是在于
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.36,0:24:13.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们无懈可击
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.26,0:24:16.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,物理学家的工作就是发现这些定律
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.26,0:24:19.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,定律不随文化的不同而改变
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.23,0:24:20.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也不随时间而改变
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.90,0:24:23.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,放之宇宙而皆准
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.03,0:24:26.10,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这就是为何  如同爱因斯坦指出的
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.14,0:24:29.77,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}接近光速时就出问题了
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.98,0:24:35.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,以接近光速的速度旅行
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.91,0:24:38.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就像是长生不老药
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.48,0:24:41.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的生物钟慢下来
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.49,0:24:43.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,相对于其他人来说
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.65,0:24:46.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这种现象或许可以为我们人类
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.32,0:24:48.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,只能活1个世纪左右的人类
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.39,0:24:50.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,提供一个可行的恒星间旅行的方案
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.83,0:24:52.96,Chinese,,0,0,0,,时空魔法大戏
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.00,0:24:55.40,Chinese,,0,0,0,,精彩纷呈
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.36,0:25:07.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}19世纪的天文学家 威廉·赫歇尔
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.29,0:25:09.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}喜欢和他的儿子约翰 分享
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.60,0:25:11.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}宇宙中的奇迹
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.44,0:25:25.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我有个朋友  很聪明的家伙
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.88,0:25:28.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,天文学家 也是里兹的牧师
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.05,0:25:30.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,名叫 约翰·米切尔
Dialogue: 0,0:25:30.78,0:25:33.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你还是婴儿时 他就过世了
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.39,0:25:35.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,愿他安息
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.32,0:25:37.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他相信有些星星
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.39,0:25:39.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,虽然看不到
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.39,0:25:42.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,却确实存在 但是我们永远无法看到
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.73,0:25:46.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,米切尔叫它们 暗星
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.83,0:25:49.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,恕我直言 父亲
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.97,0:25:52.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你的朋友肯定弄错了
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.57,0:25:54.21,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果没人能看到
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.24,0:25:57.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们怎么能知道它们确实存在
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.58,0:26:01.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你看到留下脚印的人了吗
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.08,0:26:04.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,没 怎么了
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.58,0:26:05.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我没看到
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.58,0:26:08.42,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但你知道他们确实存在
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.44,0:26:28.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}约翰·米切尔是最伟大的科学家之一
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.34,0:26:30.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}你可能从没听说过
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.71,0:26:33.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他生活工作于18世纪的英格兰
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.35,0:26:37.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}现在也没有他的画像存世
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.05,0:26:39.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}有人曾经形容他
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.55,0:26:41.19,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}胖胖的黝黑小矮人
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.22,0:26:44.76,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}胖胖的黝黑小矮人
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.79,0:26:47.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}米切尔设想一个巨大的恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.56,0:26:51.03,Chinese,,0,0,0,,质量巨大到 即使光线
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.06,0:26:53.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也无法逃离它的重力吸引
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.63,0:26:55.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你能找到暗星吗
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.57,0:26:58.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你无法用肉眼直接看见它
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.47,0:27:00.94,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但它可能留下某种足迹
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.97,0:27:02.94,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在宇宙这个沙滩上
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.98,0:27:05.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,米切尔认为我们或许可以侦测到
Dialogue: 0,0:27:05.41,0:27:08.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,某些暗星 因为它们巨大的引力
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.81,0:27:10.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果一个暗星 碰巧伴随着一个
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.22,0:27:12.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,稍小些 会发光的星星
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.49,0:27:15.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那颗星星以紧密的轨道
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.55,0:27:18.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,环绕着 看不见的东西运行
Dialogue: 0,0:27:18.42,0:27:19.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,即使我们看不到
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.93,0:27:21.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们也知道 有个质量超级巨大的
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.66,0:27:23.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,东西在那里
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.33,0:27:24.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,暗星
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.83,0:27:28.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,或者叫 黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.77,0:27:31.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,黑洞长什么样子
Dialogue: 0,0:27:31.50,0:27:33.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它的里面是什么样子的
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.67,0:27:35.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们以后会提到  但是首先
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.01,0:27:39.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们在我的家乡稍作休息
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.35,0:27:41.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}纽约
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.58,0:27:42.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这地方在我来看
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.95,0:27:45.98,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}所有的一切都在不停的运动
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.02,0:27:48.72,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我在这里住了大半辈子
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.75,0:27:50.82,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}总有新鲜事物
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.86,0:27:53.66,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但有一样从来不变 重力
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.69,0:27:55.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,重力在过去的45亿年间
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.76,0:27:58.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一直保持不变
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.20,0:28:01.33,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果 今天 我们可以改变它
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.37,0:28:03.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}重力受时空影响
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.20,0:28:05.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}会发生畸变
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.20,0:28:07.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}如同爱因斯坦提出的理论
Dialogue: 0,0:28:07.21,0:28:09.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,空间可以膨胀和收缩
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.11,0:28:10.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,无限弯曲
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.22,0:28:18.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}如果地球的体积和密度
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.55,0:28:20.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}有细微的不同
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.05,0:28:21.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它的重力也会不同
Dialogue: 0,0:28:21.89,0:28:23.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有无限的可能性
Dialogue: 0,0:28:23.96,0:28:25.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,纽约人在这里感受到的
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.83,0:28:27.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,重力单位
Dialogue: 0,0:28:27.39,0:28:29.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们称为 1g
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.80,0:28:38.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,假设我们取消一条街上的重力
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.58,0:28:46.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}运动中的人和物体
Dialogue: 0,0:28:46.51,0:28:48.65,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}就会向上飞去
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.69,0:29:00.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果我把重力加大到
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.09,0:29:02.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}比方说 8或者9g
Dialogue: 0,0:29:02.66,0:29:04.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,和谐起见
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.20,0:29:06.66,Chinese,,0,0,0,,把人拿开
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.83,0:29:09.57,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这个重力和战斗机飞行员
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.60,0:29:12.34,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}高速转弯时承受的重力相当
Dialogue: 0,0:29:12.37,0:29:14.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,几分钟内 还不会使你受伤
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.17,0:29:16.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是绝不会舒服
Dialogue: 0,0:29:16.78,0:29:19.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在10万g时
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.45,0:29:21.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}消防栓也被自身的重量
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.38,0:29:23.98,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}压扁了
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.02,0:29:25.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,几百万g
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.79,0:29:28.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光线也会被拉弯
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.52,0:29:31.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光线依然保持恒速
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.12,0:29:33.12,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但它无法逃逸
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.13,0:29:36.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,米切尔说的暗星
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.40,0:29:38.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们称为黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:29:38.63,0:29:42.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最近的一个 或许比想象的要近
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.01,0:29:52.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}不是每个恒星都会变成黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.61,0:29:55.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}只有千分之一的质量足够大
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.66,0:29:58.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}最近的一个 可能距离地球不到100光年
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.97,0:30:03.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,黑洞不是科幻小说里的宇宙吸尘器
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.26,0:30:06.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们不会到处吞噬
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.10,0:30:07.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你得去找它们
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.94,0:30:09.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是如果你去了
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.54,0:30:12.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可就是有去无回
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.14,0:30:18.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,刚才那是我们在抵抗上百万g的重力
Dialogue: 0,0:30:18.88,0:30:22.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,别忘了 那家伙可以吞噬光线
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.32,0:30:24.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们不能靠的太近
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.66,0:30:30.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当巨大的恒星消耗完它们的核燃料
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.49,0:30:32.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们不再保持高温
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.16,0:30:34.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,以抵消自身向内的引力
Dialogue: 0,0:30:34.96,0:30:38.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,质量最大的恒星塌陷
Dialogue: 0,0:30:38.73,0:30:40.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,没有光亮 只留下重力
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.90,0:30:44.37,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这个黑洞将一个超巨星的萎缩的尸体
Dialogue: 0,0:30:44.41,0:30:46.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}隐藏其中
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.17,0:30:48.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}恒星本身可能萎缩到
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.31,0:30:50.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}比黑洞还小
Dialogue: 0,0:30:50.51,0:30:53.65,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}只有64公里宽
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.52,0:30:58.72,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是发现的第一个黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.75,0:31:00.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,天鹅座X-1
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.02,0:31:03.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们在地球上是怎么发现
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.42,0:31:06.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这么小 这么暗 这么远的 东西
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.49,0:31:11.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们通过另一种光 X光
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.83,0:31:14.57,Chinese,,0,0,0,,X光中 我们看不到蓝色的星星了
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.60,0:31:18.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为它的表面温度只有微温的3万度
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.27,0:31:20.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而黑洞周围的气体圆盘
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.88,0:31:25.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在X光中发出耀眼的光芒 温度高达1亿度
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.71,0:31:27.51,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如同威廉·赫歇尔所发现的
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.55,0:31:32.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,很多恒星都有亲密的小伙伴  组成联星系统
Dialogue: 0,0:31:32.29,0:31:34.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但如果其中一个异常巨大
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.56,0:31:36.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,另一个比较小
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.52,0:31:39.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,小的这个可以吞噬它兄弟的
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.03,0:31:42.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大气层
Dialogue: 0,0:31:42.46,0:31:46.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这种神经病关系可以持续几百万年
Dialogue: 0,0:31:46.73,0:31:50.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,较大恒星的大气层被抽到炽热耀眼的吸积盘上
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.74,0:31:53.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,吸积盘不停自转
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.57,0:31:56.61,Chinese,,0,0,0,,并且漩涡式的进入黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.64,0:32:00.21,Chinese,,0,0,0,,势不可挡的重力不断加速蓝色星星的气体
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.25,0:32:01.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,将其卷入死亡漩涡
Dialogue: 0,0:32:01.72,0:32:04.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,跨过时空的界限
Dialogue: 0,0:32:04.49,0:32:06.05,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一去不复返
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.09,0:32:09.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这至关重要的界限将黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:32:09.56,0:32:13.03,Chinese,,0,0,0,,与宇宙的其他部分隔离开  被称为 事件视界
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.06,0:32:15.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在我们看来 吸积盘中的物质
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.93,0:32:18.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在靠近视界时慢下来
Dialogue: 0,0:32:18.27,0:32:20.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但绝不接触它
Dialogue: 0,0:32:20.74,0:32:23.30,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}如果你站在大气漩涡上
Dialogue: 0,0:32:23.34,0:32:25.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我并不建议这么做
Dialogue: 0,0:32:25.17,0:32:28.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,几秒钟就会越过事件视界
Dialogue: 0,0:32:28.18,0:32:33.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,进入到 从没人回来的 未知国度
Dialogue: 0,0:32:42.36,0:32:45.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们搜索了几十个星系的中心
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.26,0:32:49.40,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在每个里面都能找到 一个质量超级大的黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.43,0:32:53.83,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的银河系也不例外
Dialogue: 0,0:32:53.87,0:32:57.77,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}最靠近银河系中心的恒星运动的速度
Dialogue: 0,0:32:57.81,0:33:00.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}超过每小时4千万公里
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.04,0:33:05.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它们怎么会运动的这么快
Dialogue: 0,0:33:05.88,0:33:07.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,唯一合理的解释是
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.62,0:33:09.95,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}银河系中央存在着
Dialogue: 0,0:33:09.98,0:33:14.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}质量等于4百万个太阳的物体
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.49,0:33:17.96,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这4百万个太阳发出的光去哪里了
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.99,0:33:19.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,既然我们看不见
Dialogue: 0,0:33:19.46,0:33:22.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它一定是被禁锢在黑洞里了
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.67,0:33:31.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球离得很远 很安全
Dialogue: 0,0:33:31.91,0:33:35.08,Chinese,,0,0,0,,其他的世界或许没有这么幸运
Dialogue: 0,0:33:37.41,0:33:40.05,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果你能穿过事件视界
Dialogue: 0,0:33:40.08,0:33:41.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,却还活着
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.92,0:33:43.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你可以回头看
Dialogue: 0,0:33:43.48,0:33:46.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,宇宙的整部未来史都会
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.49,0:33:48.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,展现在你眼前
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.53,0:33:53.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,怎么会的
Dialogue: 0,0:33:53.09,0:33:54.83,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为 时空受到
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.86,0:33:57.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,黑洞的极度重力影响而扭曲
Dialogue: 0,0:33:57.27,0:34:00.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,时间被拉伸至极致
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.60,0:34:05.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但你面前会是何种景象呢
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.94,0:34:08.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我提前警告你
Dialogue: 0,0:34:08.61,0:34:11.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们说的是未经涉足过的科学领域
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.45,0:34:15.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那里可能有我们未知的物理定律
Dialogue: 0,0:34:15.38,0:34:17.95,Chinese,,0,0,0,,支配着黑洞中央的事情
Dialogue: 0,0:34:20.12,0:34:22.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在下一个爱因斯坦出现前
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.56,0:34:25.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们来做个思想实验吧
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.53,0:34:29.76,Chinese,,0,0,0,,18世纪的约翰 米切尔
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.80,0:34:31.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是靠它想象出 暗星
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.97,0:34:35.30,Chinese,,0,0,0,,爱因斯坦也是这么想出他的...
Dialogue: 0,0:35:27.37,0:35:30.77,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}父亲 你相信有鬼魂吗
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.81,0:35:34.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我不信有 人类的鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.05,0:35:35.61,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}完全不信
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.65,0:35:38.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但是 向上看 儿子
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.82,0:35:41.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}满天都是鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:35:44.09,0:35:47.12,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}你如果去过黑洞还能活着回来
Dialogue: 0,0:35:47.16,0:35:48.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}你可能会发现
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.73,0:35:51.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}我们宇宙中的其他时间和空间
Dialogue: 0,0:35:51.23,0:35:54.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}先不提 相对论的第一条戒律
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.40,0:35:57.33,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}汝不可超越光速
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.00,0:36:02.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}太空中没有什么速度可以比光速快
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.27,0:36:04.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}但太空并不空旷
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.74,0:36:09.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}空间可以延伸 收缩  被扭曲
Dialogue: 0,0:36:09.35,0:36:13.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}那样的话 时间也会被扭曲
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.75,0:36:20.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,爱因斯坦发现 空间和时间 只是
Dialogue: 0,0:36:20.53,0:36:23.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一个事物的两个方面  时空
Dialogue: 0,0:36:23.76,0:36:26.33,Chinese,,0,0,0,,时空本身可以被任意弯曲
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.36,0:36:29.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,用任意速度带你去任意地方
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.70,0:36:33.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,黑洞可能是不同宇宙间的隧道
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.49,0:36:52.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}通过这种星际间的交通系统 你可以
Dialogue: 0,0:36:52.29,0:36:54.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}达到时空的最远端
Dialogue: 0,0:36:54.39,0:36:57.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}或许其他更惊人的地方
Dialogue: 0,0:37:00.40,0:37:03.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,或许是个完全不一样的宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:37:03.90,0:37:06.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是一个黑洞怎么能容纳整个宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.74,0:37:11.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}黑洞只是我们宇宙中的很小一部分
Dialogue: 0,0:37:11.48,0:37:14.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这又是一个时空变出的戏法
Dialogue: 0,0:37:14.58,0:37:17.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,黑洞无与伦比的引力
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.52,0:37:21.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,可以将整个宇宙的空间扭曲并塞进去
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.76,0:37:32.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们现在受到的引力 或许很强
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.16,0:37:33.83,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但却无法和
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.87,0:37:36.30,Chinese,,0,0,0,,萎缩恒星内部的引力 相提并论
Dialogue: 0,0:37:36.33,0:37:38.40,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}据我们所知
Dialogue: 0,0:37:38.44,0:37:42.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}当超大恒星萎缩成黑洞时
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.17,0:37:43.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}中心产生极大的密度和压力
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.94,0:37:48.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}如同诞生宇宙的大爆炸
Dialogue: 0,0:37:48.71,0:37:50.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}于是黑洞内诞生了一个宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:37:50.45,0:37:52.98,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这宇宙可能会产生它自己的黑洞
Dialogue: 0,0:37:53.02,0:37:55.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这些黑洞 又会产生其他的宇宙
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.79,0:38:03.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,或许我们的宇宙就是如此
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.37,0:38:17.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,众所周知
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.21,0:38:21.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果你想知道黑洞里面有什么
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.48,0:38:23.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,只要看看四周
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.39,0:38:31.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}威廉·赫歇尔发现了 太阳
Dialogue: 0,0:38:31.06,0:38:34.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}带着它的行星们 在银河系中运行
Dialogue: 0,0:38:34.56,0:38:37.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他的儿子有什么成就呢
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.16,0:38:40.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他成为了一位伟大的科学家
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.17,0:38:43.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在他父亲的基础上 他所得出的外太空观测结果
Dialogue: 0,0:38:43.84,0:38:46.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}成为了星系标准目录的依据
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.50,0:38:48.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}沿用至今
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.44,0:38:51.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}当威廉身体不好时  约翰陪着他
Dialogue: 0,0:38:51.68,0:38:53.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}在望远镜旁 度过长夜
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.68,0:38:55.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}帮他观测恒星
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.51,0:39:00.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}父亲过世后 约翰写下墓志铭
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.52,0:39:03.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他推倒天堂的围墙
Dialogue: 0,0:39:15.20,0:39:16.83,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}约翰经常缅怀
Dialogue: 0,0:39:16.87,0:39:18.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}与他父亲度过的那些夏日夜晚
Dialogue: 0,0:39:18.94,0:39:23.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}这或许就是为何 他要寻找保存过去的方法
Dialogue: 0,0:39:25.11,0:39:26.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}约翰·赫歇尔 是一种展现形式的时间旅行的
Dialogue: 0,0:39:26.88,0:39:28.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}创始人之一
Dialogue: 0,0:39:28.95,0:39:32.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}一种保留光线和记忆的办法
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.82,0:39:35.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}他为它选择了一个名字
Dialogue: 0,0:39:35.29,0:39:37.72,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}摄影
Dialogue: 0,0:39:42.56,0:39:44.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你这么想
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.13,0:39:46.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,摄影是时间旅行的一种形式
Dialogue: 0,0:39:46.97,0:39:50.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,几百年前的人注视着我们
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.47,0:39:52.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,光线勾勒出的鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:39:52.90,0:39:55.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不难想象 在不远的未来
Dialogue: 0,0:39:55.74,0:39:57.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们可以保留过去
Dialogue: 0,0:39:57.51,0:39:59.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,以三维立体的形式
Dialogue: 0,0:39:59.74,0:40:03.08,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们可以走进一段记忆
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.82,0:40:10.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}或许不能回到过去的时间
Dialogue: 0,0:40:10.66,0:40:14.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但可能 有一天 可以将过去带来现在
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.19,0:40:19.40,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是我过去的一刻
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.43,0:40:20.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就像约翰·赫歇尔
Dialogue: 0,0:40:20.93,0:40:23.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我记得幼年的我
Dialogue: 0,0:40:23.77,0:40:26.34,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1975年12月20号
Dialogue: 0,0:40:26.37,0:40:28.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,纽约的一个雪天
Dialogue: 0,0:40:28.87,0:40:32.14,Chinese,,0,0,0,,生命旅程的一个拐点
Dialogue: 0,0:40:32.18,0:40:35.08,Chinese,,0,0,0,,让我有机会站在这里
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.11,0:40:37.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那天我遇到了卡尔·萨根
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.72,0:40:44.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\i1}就如同天空中那些星星的鬼魂
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.46,0:40:53.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,即使已经消亡 但星光依然照耀我们
